<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Appeals Against WTO ruling on Dairy Subsidy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Canadian government Thursday
launched a formal appeal against an earlier World Trade
Organization (WTO) ruling over the dairy export subsidy.
</P>
<P>
"Canada believes that its dairy industry pricing practices
conform with WTO rules," Agriculture Minister Lyle Vanclief said at
the launching of the appeal.
</P>
<P>
He vowed to "work closely with the industry to make a strong
case before the Appellate Body."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Canadian International Trade Minister Sergio Marchi
made it clear that the appeal "demonstrates our firm commitment to
Canada's dairy industry."
</P>
<P>
"We have been working closely with the provinces and the
industry to prepare Canada's submission, which we are delivering
to the WTO on July 19," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The WTO decided in March this year that Canada's dairy pricing
system for certain exports to be an export subsidy and demanded
changes be made by Canada in its tariff rate quota for fluid milk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
