<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush to Forgo Federal Matching Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Republican presidential
front-runner George W. Bush said Thursday that he would not accept
federal matching funds for his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
The Texas governor, who has raised 37 million dollars in the
first six months of 1999, said that if he accepted the matching
funds, his campaign would have been restricted by spending limits
in early states like Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
"After looking at the numbers, cash on hand of 30 million dollars,
I've decided not to accept federal matching funds during the course
of this campaign," Bush said while campaigning in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
"You've got limits that constrain a candidate," Bush said. "I
want to be in a position to respond. I want to be in a position to
plan, and I want to be in a position to plan according to need."
</P>
<P>
By forgoing matching funds, Bush will be able to spend as much
as he wants in pursuit of the Republican presidential nomination,
according to the rules of the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
But he will still have to abide by contribution limits of 1,000
dollars per person or 5,000 dollars per political action
committee.
</P>
<P>
With the withdrawal of Representative John Kasich of Ohio
from the presidential campaign and the departure of Senator
Robert C. Smith from the Republican Party, there are still 10
vying for their party's nomination as presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
They are George W. Bush; Senator McCain of Arizona; Elizabeth
Dole, the former president of the Red Cross; former Vice
President Dan Quayle; Senator Orrin G Hatch of Utah; Lamar
Alexander, a former education secretary; Steve Forbes, a
multimillionaire publisher; Alan Keyes, a former diplomat; Gary
L. Bauer, the former head of the Family Research Council; and
Patrick J Buchanan, the conservative commentator. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
