<HEADLINE> Clinton Promises to "Walk With" Israel in Peace Search </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Thursday welcomed Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak in the White
House Rose Garden, saying the United States "will walk with you"
in search for peace in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"As Israel again walks bravely down the path of peace, America
will walk with you," Clinton said, referring to the historic White
House handshake between Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and the
late Israeli leader Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
"As we have seen before at this house... what first seems
unlikely -- even impossible -- can actually become reality when
the will for peace is strong," Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
Barak said he would "inject new momentum into the peace process
and to put it back on all tracks."
</P>
<P>
"It is our intention to inject new momentum into the peace
process and to put it back on all tracks," he said. "For this we
need American leadership and support all along the way."
</P>
<P>
He said the United States could contribute to the process "more
as a facilitator than as a kind of policeman, judge and arbitrator
at the same time."
</P>
<P>
Barak said Israel would live up to all agreements, including
last October's Wye agreement on Israel's further pullback in the
West Bank. He also promised to pursue agreements with with Syria
and Lebanon, and he said he was prepared to meet with Syrian
President Hafez Assad. "It takes two to tango. I am ready," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
