<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Committed to Implementing Peace Pact in DRC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan State Minister for Foreign
Affairs Amama Mbabazi said here Thursday that his country is
committed to implementing the ceasefire agreement in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Mbabazi, who had been taking part in the whole process of the
negotiations for the agreement, stressed at a press conference
that a kind of mechanism had been established to handle the
security concerns of the DRC and its neighboring countries
including Uganda.
</P>
<P>
The main problem, said Mbabazi, is that the DRC rebels, the
Congolese Rally for Democracy (RCD) and the Movement for the
Liberation of Congo (MLC) , were not able to sign the agreement
immediately because of differences between the two factions of
RCD, which differed over who should represent them in signing the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
Uganda hopes the rebel groups in DRC would iron out their
differences and sign the agreement as soon as possible in the
interests of peace in DRC and security of its neighbors, said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
"Uganda will not stand by any faction of the Congolese rebels",
Mbabazi said, adding "as I know Rwanda takes the same position
with Uganda". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
