<HEADLINE> DRC Rebels Violate Ceasefire Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African Development
Community (SADC) Task Force headquarters in Kinshasa, capital of
the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), said Thursday that the
rebels were not committed to peace.
</P>
<P>
"SADC Task Force Headquarters wishes to announce that while the
 regional and international community are working hard to see that
the war in the DRC comes to an end, it is becoming evident that
the rebels are not committed to peace.
</P>
<P>
"There is total lack of goodwill and commitment on the part of
rebels as evidenced by their failure to sign the Lusaka ceasefire
accord," the Task Force said in a statement released here in the
Zimbabwean capital.
</P>
<P>
It said since the ceasefire agreement was signed last Saturday
in Lusaka, Zambia, the rebels had violated the pact.
</P>
<P>
These included rebel attacks on allied forces Monday, Tuesday
and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Task Force said it did not initiate any attacks in all
these incidents.
</P>
<P>
"While we uphold the ceasefire agreement, we would like to
warn the rebels that once attacked we shall retaliate with the
means available at our disposal, and they shall be held
responsible for the consequences," said the Task Force.
</P>
<P>
In some parts of the battlefield, the rebels and their allies
had already started movements which were beginning to threaten
various main supply routes, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The Task Force said efforts to ensure that these routes were
secured would be put in place accordingly, and urged the rebels
and their allies to abide by the Lusaka ceasefire accord.
</P>
</TEXT>
