<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Parliament Passes 1999 Budget Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 15 (Xinhua) -- After four consecutive days of
debate, Lebanese Parliament Thursday night endorsed the
long-awaited 1999 fiscal budget.
</P>
<P>
In the 128-seat parliament, a total of 73 deputies voted for
the bill, which was approved by the cabinet in April, with 42
members against it and 13 others abstaining from voting.
</P>
<P>
The budget pegged revenue for 1999 at 3.2 billion dollars, and
spending at 5.5 billion dollars, higher compared with 2.9 billion
dollars and 5.2 billion dollars respectively for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The bill also introduced a whopping 30 percent tax on
alcoholic beverages, tobacco and other non-essential commodities
and increased gosoline prices by 2,000 Lebanese pounds (about 1.3
dollars) per 20 liters.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese government is struggling to bring public debt down
from 123 percent of Gross Domestic Product (GDP) to 98 percent by
2003, and cut the budget deficit to five percent of GDP from its
current 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 MPs had asked to address the house in the
debate which was televised live by Beirut's six state-run and
private networks.
</P>
<P>
Many MPs exploited the discussion of budget to unleash a
vast range of attacks against the government of Salim Hoss
in order to please public opinion in the run-up to next
year's parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
But observers had predicted that the budget will finally pass
with a handsome majority because Syria will not allow a
no-confidence vote leading to the domestic political disputes in
advance of the anticipated resumption of the Arab-Israeli peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
With 35,00 troops stationed in Lebanon as peacekeepers, Syria
is the country's undisputed power broker. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
