<HEADLINE> Hijacker Killed as Greek Police Storm Bus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Albanian hijacker armed with a
hand grenade was killed and all five remaining hostages were
unharmed late Thursday when Greek police stormed the bus, which
had been hijacked by the Albanian since Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) quoted a police
officer as saying that the police stormed the bus immediately
after the Albanian had closed his eyes from fatigue.
</P>
<P>
The hand grenade the hijacker was holding exploded outside the
bus, which had been hijacked in Polykastro near the northern Greek
city of Thessaloniki.
</P>
<P>
The attack came following the failure of the negotiations
between the Greek police and the 28-year-old Albanian hijacker,
Aleksandr Nana, who demanded a ransom of 250 million drachmas
(about 793,650 U.S. dollars) and safe passage to Albania with all
his hostages, six passengers and the bus driver, the semi-official
Athens News Agency (ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the afternoon, the hostage-taker had released two of
the hostages.
</P>
<P>
The intercity bus had been since late Wednesday blocked by
police outside Florina, a some half-hour drive from the border
with neighboring Albania.
</P>
<P>
This is the second bus-hijacking incident in Greece in less
than two months. On May 29, an Albanian armed with a hand grenade
and assault rifle also hijacked a Greek bus with passengers on
board near Thessaloniki. After being paid a ransom of 50 million
drachmas (about 158,730 dollars), the 24-year-old Albanian forced
the driver to cross over into Albania where he and a Greek hostage
were shot to death by Albanian police. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
