<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Irish PM Urges New N.Irish Peace Push </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern
said Thursday he was disappointed Northern Ireland's political
parties had failed to establish a new power-sharing government,
but he urged all sides not to lose heart.
</P>
<P>
"People should not allow themselves to be deflected or
disheartened," Ahern was quoted by a Reuters report filed from
Dublin as saying in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Ahern and his British counterpart, Tony Blair, who were leading
architects of the last year's Good Friday agreement, are to meet
next week to prepare the way for a review of the pact aimed at
getting it back on track by September, according to earlier
reports.
</P>
<P>
"The government remains determined that, working closely with
the British government and the parties, a way can and will be
found to implement the agreement in full," Ahern said.
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland's fragile peace process suffered a heavy blow
Thursday after the main Protestant Ulster Unionist Party (UUP)
refused to sit in a regional government with the Catholic Sinn
Fein without a clear promise to disarm by the Irish Republican
Army (IRA).
</P>
<P>
The boycott raised doubts that the landmark peace deal would
ever overcome the issue of whether IRA guerrillas, who waged a
long conflict against British rule of the province, should disarm
before or after an all-party government is up and running.
</P>
<P>
Despite the setback, Ahern said the government believed the
Good Friday agreement remained the only way forward and that he
believed the Northern Irish society wanted to move ahead.
</P>
<P>
"It remains the unalterable objective of the Irish government,
working with the British Government and the Northern Ireland
parties, to see the will of the people in both parts of Ireland
implemented as expressed in the referendums of May 22, 1998,"
Ahern was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Irish prime minister said he regretted the resignation of
top Catholic leader Seamus Mallon as deputy first minister
designate and praised his "tireless work... political skill,
wisdom and integrity." He said he looked forward to Mallon
continuing to play a central role in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Mallon, one of the province's most respected politicians and
deputy leader of the Social Democratic and Labor Party, resigned
Thursday, saying the UUP was using the crisis to bleed the peace
process dry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
