<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique, Portugal Sign Deal on Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The governments of Mozambique and
Portugal signed here Thursday an agreement on health cooperation,
under which the latter will provide 12 million U.S. dollars to
assist health development in three Mozambican provinces.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Portuguese Health Minister Maria de Belem Roseira and
her Mozambican counterpart Aurelio Zilhao signed the deal, the
Mozambique News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Roseira said after the signing ceremony that the deal is the
result of a package of agreements between the two countries
reached in March this year.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the 12 million dollars will be helpful to alleviate
the difficulties facing the country's medical institutions," she
said.
</P>
<P>
However, the visiting minister said an institution made up of
representatives from the two countries will be set up to enhance
transparency and administer the use of the money.
</P>
<P>
The money, according to Zilhao, will be used to expand health
network as well as personnel training in Maputo and Gaza provinces
in the south, and Nampula Province in the north.
</P>
<P>
Roseira arrived here Monday for a four-day visit to Mozambique.
 During her stay, she also visited the health institutions in the
three provinces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
