<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Asks Members To Show Opinion On GMO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission Thursday
called on the European Union (EU)'s member states to demonstrate
their concerns over the genetically modified organisms (GMO) since
some EU nations are calling for stopping the GMO approvals.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive said its commissioner for the environment,
Ritt Bjerregaard, has written to "the concerned member states to
get a clear picture of their intentions with regard to the
GMO-dossiers these same member states have submitted for
approval."
</P>
<P>
"In particular the commission would be interested in any
intentions to withdraw pending notifications," the executive said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The commission said France supported by some other delegations,
at an environmental meeting on June 24-25, put forward a
declaration calling for a suspension of GMO approvals.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the declaration, Ms. Bjerregaard asked the member
states in question to "indicate the approach your government
intends to adopt to these pending notifications, and to any new
applications which may be received, and what repercussions you
consider will follow. In particular, I would be interested to know
whether and when you intend to consult the notifiers with a view
to withdrawing the notification."
</P>
<P>
The commission believed that France's declaration underlined
the importance that the commission presents rules without delay
for ensuring labeling and traceability of GMO's and derived
products.
</P>
<P>
The commission said Bjerregaard asks member states concerned to
provide full details of their position, and in particular of any
specific changes they may wish to see to a certain decision on GMO
labeling.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive, mainly responsible for proposing and
enforcing legislation, said it agrees fully with the member states
about the need to put in place a more transparent framework and to
restore public and market confidence in GMO.
</P>
<P>
However, the general suspension of new or existing
authorizations does not appear to be a practical way forward; the
commission has a clear legal obligation to pursue the procedures
set out in the relative EU directive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
