<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-15 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> mee071516hke - Israel's Unemployment Remains Stable in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Israel's unemployment remain
stable for the first time this year, with 161,100 people seeking
jobs in June.
</P>
<P>
Summing up the unemployment in the first half of 1999, the
Israeli Central Bureau of Statistics announced on Thursday the
number of job seekers rose by 3.5 percent, or 5,600 people were
newly unemployed.
</P>
<P>
It also said that since the beginning of the year, the number
of layoffs reached more than 80,000 and the wave of dismissals is
continuing.
</P>
<P>
Since the former Likud government introduced a restrictive
economic policy in 1996, the high unemployment rate has become a
serious headache for the country.
</P>
<P>
Before and after the general elections this May, Israel's new
Prime Minister Ehud Barak has repeatedly pledged to find a way to
decrease unemployment effectively.
</P>
<P>
Barak promised that 30,000 new jobs will be created after he
took office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
