<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Recent studies by the Iraqi Oil Ministry showed that
there are oil and gas reserves in the western desert areas of
Iraq, the Arabic economic daily Al-Alam Al-Youm on Thursday quoted
Director General of the Iraqi Oil Prospection Co. Ibrahim
Abdul-Karim as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the Iraqi official did not disclose the volume of the
newly-discovered reserves in an area 300 kilometers northwest of
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Iraq's oil reserve hits 112 billion barrels and is the second
largest in the world after Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Iraq will soon restore its status as the second largest oil
exporter in the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OPEC) for the first time since the 1991 Gulf war, said the
official.
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Chief of the Iraqi Industry Federation Adnan
Al-Hamidawi has declared the initiation of 10 share-holding firms
in the industrial sector.
</P>
<P>
The firms will be engaged in the fields of machine-building ,
auto spare parts, textile, engineering, iron and steel, building
materials, glass and ceramics, the Al-Alam Al-Youm daily on
Thursday quoted Al-Hamidawi as saying.
</P>
<P>
The move is part of Iraq's efforts to support the private
industrial sector and set in motion the private factories that
have stopped operation since the 1991 Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi officials said that over 20,000 factories stopped
operation due to the U.N.-imposed embargo against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Unexpected rainfalls partially have saved the rice
crop in northern Iran from drought.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Agriculture Corporation in Jilan Province
Ismail Nigarsh said that it started raining on Tuesday, thus
saving 25 percent of the rice crop in the province overlooking the
Caspian Sea.
</P>
<P>
The rains saved 30,000 hectares of rice and irrigated other
55,000 hectares which were threatened by the drought.
</P>
<P>
Some 11,000 hectares of rice were damaged by drought, the
severest in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
MUSCAT -- The Central Bank of Oman (CBO) said the country's
gross domestic product (GDP) went down by 10.2 percent in 1998
compared to the growth rate of 3.4 percent in 1997 due to the
global economic slump and the oil price decline, the Al-Hayat
daily reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The primary estimate of the GDP, according to a CBO report,
indicates that the oil sector contribution to the GDP declined by
32 percent while the share of non-oil sectors such as agriculture
and services grew by 4.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
All the economic sectors of the country were affected by the
oil price slump in the world market, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The average price of the Omani crude oil retreated 36 cents to
stand at 11.92 U.S. dollars per barrel in 1998 after it reached
18.82 dollars in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
