<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Sets up Northern Free Trade Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has set up a new free trade
zone in the north of the country to attract Arab and foreign
investments, an official announced on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Karim Munshid al-Asadi, director of the free trade zone, said
that the zone is located 20 kilometers north of Mosul, the capital
city of Neineva province, and has convenient communications with
Syria, Jordan and Turkey, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The annual rent for per square meter of the zone is three
U.S. dollars in paved areas, two dollars in unpaved areas and 10
dollars for roofed warehouses.
</P>
<P>
He said that all commodities except weapons and polluted
materials can be traded freely in the zone and will be duty-free,
and investors can open foreign currency accounts in designated
banks and send their money to their home countries.
</P>
<P>
The zone will provide necessary services such as security
measures, civil defense, continuous electricity power, sewage,
restaurant, transportation and communications offices, he added.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the zone will help break the
U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq in 1990 and develop its economy by
attracting foreign investments and new technologies, said the
official.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Iraq established a free trade zone in the
south of the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
