<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France, Bahrain Intend to Sign Defense Cooperation Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- France and the Gulf emirate of
Bahrain intend to sign a defense cooperation treaty soon, French
presidential spokeswoman Catherine Colonna announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The intention was expressed by both French President Jacques
Chirac and visiting Bahraini Emir Sheikh Hamad Ben Issa Al-Khalifa
during their talks, said the spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
French and Bahraini officials are working out the details of
such a defense treaty, she added.
</P>
<P>
Chirac and Sheikh Hamad also discussed the situation of Iran
and Iraq and the Middle East peace process, according to the
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
They expressed concern over the long absence of a U.N.
mechanism to supervise disarmament in Iraq, and agreed that the
United Nations Security Council should continue to discuss this
issue and find a solution to the impasse, said Colonna.
</P>
<P>
The two heads of state also share the same hope for a
resumption of the Israel-Arab peace process and estimate that the
conditions are ready for it now, she said.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Hamad is on his first state visit to a country outside
the Arab world since he inherited in March the throne from his
father, the late Sheikh Issa ben Salman Al-Khalifa.
</P>
<P>
France has signed a contract with Bahrain on building a sea
water processing plant, and is considering some other projects in
oil, electricity and civil aviation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
