<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Welcomes Accord Between Britain, Argentina </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
welcomed the agreement Britain and Argentina reached to reduce
tension over the disputed Malvinas Islands.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Thursday the accord
demonstrated "the determination of both Argentina and the United
Kingdom to work cooperatively and constructively to promote the
well-being and stability of the region."
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, Britain and Argentina agreed on a package of
measures, including lifting of a ban on Argentines visiting the
islands, resumption of direct flights from Chile and cooperation
on fish preservation in the South Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
Lockhart said Clinton congratulated British Prime Minister Tony
Blair and Argentine President Carlos Menem on reaching the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
The White House spokesman's statement referred the islands to
both the Falklands, which Britain called, and the Malvinas.
</P>
<P>
The pact marked the most significant thaw in relations between
the two nations since they went to war over the islands that
Argentina calls the Malvinas in 1982. 
</P>
</TEXT>
