<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Prices Remain Unchanged in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Labor Department reported
Thursday that consumer prices held steady in June for the second
straight month.
</P>
<P>
The Department said the Consumer Price Index (CPI), the most
closely watched gauge of inflation, was flat in June as it was in
May.
</P>
<P>
The June's showing is the best one on inflation in 13 years,
economists said.
</P>
<P>
The last time prices showed no increase for two straight months
was in 1986, when for three consecutive months the CPI actually
fell.
</P>
<P>
The good performance on consumer prices, which followed
Wednesday's report that prices at the wholesale level actually
fell 0.1 percent, was certain to calm fears about inflation that
had been generated when prices at the retail and wholesale level
spiked in April.
</P>
<P>
With inflation pressures now moderating, some economists
believe Fed policy-makers will not increase rates when they meet
again next month.
</P>
<P>
Just as in May, the good showing on consumer prices in June
reflected a big drop in energy costs. Gasoline prices fell a sharp
3.2 percent last month, the most in more than two years. Gasoline
prices were down 2.7 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
The big drop in gasoline prices contributed to an overall
decline of 1.2 percent in energy costs, which followed a 1.3
percent drop in May and helped reverse a part of April's huge 6.1
percent increase.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, food prices were unchanged in June, after a 0.4
percent rise the month before. The moderation in food costs came
even though beef prices shot up 1.5 percent, the biggest increase
in more than six years. So the prices were held back by big
declines in prices of pork and fresh vegetables.
</P>
<P>
Outside the volatile food and energy sectors, price pressures
remained tame as well. The so-called "core rate" of inflation was
up only 0.1 percent in June, the same as May.
</P>
<P>
Also, apparel prices dropped 0.4 percent last month, the fifth
decline this year. Airline fares were down 4.8 percent, the
largest drop in more than three years, while new-car prices fell 0.
3 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
