<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges N.Ireland Parties to Keep Trying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States Thursday
called the collapse of Northern Ireland's peace process a setback
and urged the parties to keep trying.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously the activity of last night is a setback for the
process," White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
The peace process in Northern Island ran into an impasse after
Protestant Ulster Unionist Party leader David Trimble Thursday
rejected a peace plan put forward by leaders of Britain and
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and Irish Prime Minister
Bertie Ahern on July 2 proposed Sinn Fein would be allowed into an
executive for Northern Ireland on July 15 and Sinn Fein's military
wing -- the Irish Republic Army (IRA) will be decommissioned by
May 2000.
</P>
<P>
However, Trimble insists that Sinn Fein should not be allowed
into the government before the IRA is decommissioned.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. still hopes the parties will keep trying to resolve
their dispute. "I understand that the British government has
ordered a review of the implementation" of the Good Friday accord
reached last year between the parties, Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
He said President Bill Clinton "believes there is clearly a
mandate among all the people for peace and that the parties need
to stay at this until they find a way to solve their differences."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
