<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Jobless Claims Rise Sharply Last Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July (Xinhua) -- The number of new claims for
jobless benefits rose sharply last week to its highest level in a
month, the Labor Department reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that 310,000 people in this country filed new
claims for unemployment benefits for the week ending July 10, up
by 11,000 from the week before.
</P>
<P>
The increase, after two consecutive declines, left the claims
at their highest point since June 5 when they were at 326,000.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the four-week moving average for claims, which
smooths out week-to-week volatility, also was up to 303,250. That
was the highest level since June 26 when they were at 307,250.
</P>
<P>
Last week's increase was larger than economists had been
expecting, but still kept claims at a level indicating that the
nation's job market remains healthy.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department said Thursday that for the week ending
July 3, 12 states and territories reported declines in jobless
claims, while 39 had increases. The state data lag a week behind
the national figures.
</P>
<P>
The state with the biggest decline in applications for jobless
benefits was Florida, a decrease due to fewer layoffs in the
construction, trade and service industries as well as in
agriculture. And, the state with the biggest increase was
Missouri, an increase officials blamed on layoffs in the
automobile and transportation industries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
