<HEADLINE> U.N. Conference Reaffirms Applicability of Geneva </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations conference has
reaffirmed the applicability of the Fourth Geneva Convention to
the Occupied Palestinian Territory, including East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here Thursday at the end of the
conference, representatives from some 60 countries also reiterated
the need for full respect for the provisions of the convention in
the Palestinian territory. The 1949 pact aims to protect civilians
in times of war.
</P>
<P>
The closed-door meeting was adjourned after about 40 minutes as
the atmosphere in the Middle East was considered "improved" as a
whole, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
"We would like to see Israel actually proceed on its own to
implement the Convention, to stop settlement activities and to
proceed with the peace process," said Nabil Shaath, head of the
Palestinian delegation to the Conference of the High Contracting
Parties to the Fourth Geneva Convention.
</P>
<P>
By proposing adjournment of the U.N. conference after a token
session, Shaath said Palestinians were giving Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak, who took office a week ago, a chance to
revive peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
But the minister of planning and international cooperation in
the Palestinian Authority said that the final consensus statement
included a clause to reconvene the meeting should Israel fail to
uphold the Fourth Geneva Convention.
</P>
<P>
"And we would like to give the Israeli government an
opportunity to do so. But we would like to maintain this process
as, let's say, a last resort in case the Israeli government
continues with the settlements," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
