<HEADLINE> Cyprus' Parliament Denounces Junta Coup 25 Years Ago </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' Parliament Thursday held
an extraordinary session to denounce the military coup engineered
by the Greek military junta in July 1974 and the Turkish invasion
and occupation that followed.
</P>
<P>
The junta toppled the former president Makarios on July 15,
1974 and only five days later, Turkey invaded and occupied the
northern third of the island under the pretext of protecting the
Turkish Cypriots.
</P>
<P>
A 35,000-strong Turkish army are still stationed in the
island's northern area.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' Parliament observed a one-minute silence for those
killed during the 1974 war.
</P>
<P>
Opening the session, Parliament Speaker Spyros Kyprianou said
today's anniversary is a day for all Cypriots to undertake their
responsibilities "because the future of their children and
grandchildren is at stake."
</P>
<P>
He said that an acceptable solution of the Cyprus issue should
secure conditions of unity.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Government Spokesman Costas Serezis Thursday issued
a statement, condemning the military coup that toppled the
democratically elected government of the Cyprus' Republic 25
years ago.
</P>
<P>
Given that Cyprus is facing "a crucial period, we
must all work together jointly to achieve the necessary unity
with a view to handling effectively the future of this country,"
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
