<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gun Worries Arise From N.Irish Peace Deal Collapse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The breakdown of the Northern
Ireland peace process is ringing alarm bells in the province's
divided Catholic and Protestant communities with renewed fear that
it may signal a return to violence.
</P>
<P>
The worry is that following Thursday's breakdown in last year's
Good Friday peace agreement that silenced most of the guns, the
process has turned down a blind alley leaving the British and
Irish governments with a political firefighting exercise to chart
a way forward.
</P>
<P>
History shows hawks on both sides are always ready to swoop
during a power vacuum when political tempers and emotions rise in
the centuries-old conflict, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
"The chief worry is that, during the period of review, the
parties will re-trench their positions and paramilitaries will
seek to exploit the failure to secure political agreement," The
Belfast Telegraph warned in a front page article Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, the signs so far are considered optimistic. A
two-year-old truce by the Irish Republican Army is intact and
security experts say they do not expect the IRA to take up arms
despite political setbacks suffered by its Sinn Fein political
wing.
</P>
<P>
"There is too much invested by the Republican Movement (IRA and
Sinn Fein) in the peace process at the moment. Any violence by the
IRA would undermine political gains by Sinn Fein," Reuters quoted
Tom Brady, security affairs editor of the Irish Independent paper,
as saying.
</P>
<P>
"They will sit tight," a senior British security official was
quoted as saying about the IRA which halted a bloody onslaught
against rule from London in July 1997 to pave the way for its Sinn
Fein political wing to get a place in peace talks.
</P>
<P>
"Loyalist" splinter-groups, so-called for their determination
to resist any moves towards unity with Ireland, "are
unpredictable," the British source said.
</P>
<P>
The province's main Protestant Ulster Unionist Party (UUP),
which condemns guerrilla violence, has as much political capital
to lose as Sinn Fein if hot-headed rebels turn to the gun.
</P>
<P>
The UUP torpedoed the plans for a power-sharing provincial
government with its demands that the IRA must first hand in its
weapons.
</P>
<P>
Security experts believe the IRA has some 60 tons of armaments,
including 600 assault rifles and three tons of semtex high
explosives, stashed in bunkers in remote areas of the Irish
republic. They also are believed to have caches in Northern
Ireland itself, Reuters said.
</P>
<P>
Although Republican supporters have been angered by British
attempts to make concessions to unionists on the thorny issue of
IRA disarmament, no one is talking about going back to war. If the
IRA resumed hostilities it would immediately play into the hands
of unionists who have always been sceptical about the guerrilla
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
Crucially too, it would lead to Sinn Fein's immediate expulsion
from the peace process under the terms of the Good Friday
agreement, a Reuters analysis said.
</P>
<P>
There is some concern that while formation of the executive
would have meant sustained pressure on Sinn Fein and the IRA for
early disarmament, the collapse of the plan takes the pressure
off.
</P>
<P>
"What we worry about now is one small incident, no matter by
whom, leading to another until everyone is sucked back into
violence," Reuters quoted a politician as saying. "All sides
realize that a vacuum is a combustible, and a sharp strike by any
group runs the risk of starting a contagion." 
</P>
</TEXT>
