<HEADLINE> Clinton Urges N. Ireland Parties to Keep Trying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Thursday called the collapse of Northern Ireland's peace process a
setback and urged the parties to keep trying.
</P>
<P>
"I share the regret that the people of Ireland and Northern
Ireland feel at the setback in the peace process," Clinton said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The peace process in Northern Island ran into an impasse after
the Protestant Ulster Unionist Party leader David Trimble Thursday
rejected a peace plan put forward by leaders of Britain and
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and Irish Prime Minister
Bertie Ahern on July 2 proposed Sinn Fein would be allowed into an
executive for Northern Ireland on July 15 and Sinn Fein's military
wing -- the Irish Republic Army (IRA) will be decommissioned by
May 2000.
</P>
<P>
Clinton is still optimistic about the future of the process,
saying that "real progress" has been made on all sides toward
fulfilling the solemn commitments in the Good Friday Agreement
signed last year by the parties.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that it is possible to achieve full
implementation of this historic agreement in all its aspects by
next Spring, as contemplated by its terms," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton called upon all the parties involved to "find the way
to get the peace process back on track."
</P>
<P>
The talks broke up because Trimble insists that Sinn Fein
should not be allowed into the government before the IRA is
decommissioned.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. still hopes the parties will keep trying to resolve
their dispute. "I understand that the British government has
ordered a review of the implementation" of the Good Friday
accord, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton "believes there is clearly a mandate among all the
people for peace and that the parties need to stay at this until
they find a way to solve their differences," Lockhart said.
</P>
