<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Builds Road to Slave Town for Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania is building a
modern asphalt road from its capital Dar es Salaam to Bagamoyo,
known as a slave town in history, in a move to promote tourism.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government, in collaboration with the European
Union (EU), is helping to finance the construction of the road,
according to an EU newsletter released here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The project will give a considerable economic boost to
Bagamoyo, which has many tourist attractions reflecting different
periods of Tanzania's pre- colonial and colonial history.
</P>
<P>
As a terminal on the coast for Arab trading caravans, Bagamoyo
naturally became a holding depot for slaves brought from the
interior. The fortified house, where slaves were kept before being
led down a tunnel to the sea and the dhows waiting to ship them
across to Zanzibar, still stands.
</P>
<P>
The small town, 70 kilometers from Dar es Salaam, gives the
impression of having slept through the 20th century for lack of
economic development.
</P>
<P>
The 40-kilometer stretch, from the cement factory at Wazo Hill
to the roundabout on the outskirts of Bagamoyo, will cost 11.5
billion Tanzanian shillings (about 15.5 million U.S. dollars) to
construct. It will be financed by a grant from the Italian
government, the newsletter said.
</P>
<P>
The EU has financed the design and will finance the supervision
of works, costing one billion shillings. Construction should take
two years from May 1999 and preparatory work started at the end of
rainy season, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, repairs to the old and new Bagamoyo roads and the
road that links them in the north of Dar es Salaam, which cost one
billion shillings, are now nearing completion.
</P>
<P>
These roads were damaged during the El Nino rains of late 1997
and early 1998. Potholes have been filled, asphalt re-laid, side
drains have been cleared or newly installed, along with other
repairs to bridges and culverts.
</P>
<P>
Similar repairs are also being carried out on the road between
the Morogoro and Dodoma towns in central Tanzania at a cost of
1.3 billion shillings, according to the report that reviews EU's
efforts in rehabilitating roads in Tanzania this year.
</P>
<P>
Emergency repairs to around 170 kilometers of storm-damaged
trunk road in the northern part of the country are nearing
completion. The work of re- gravelling costs more than one
billion shillings, the newsletter said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
