<HEADLINE> More Foreigners Visit South Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The number of foreign
travellers to South Africa shot up 16 percent to 513,989 in
January compared with the same month last year, Statistics South
Africa said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The figure was boosted by an 18.6-percent rise in the number of
 travellers from the rest of Africa, against a 13-percent increase
in overseas visitors, the national statistical bureau said.
</P>
<P>
However, there was often "quite a substantial" month-to-month
variation in tourism figures and longer periods needed to be
examined before trends could be determined, it cautioned.
</P>
<P>
South Africa attracted more than 140,000 overseas travellers in
January, compared with more than 360,000 visitors from Africa.
</P>
<P>
A quarter of all offshore visitors came from Britain, followed
by Germany, the United States, the Netherlands, France, Australia,
Italy and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-eight percent of African visitors were from Lesotho,
followed by Swaziland and Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
In the same month, nearly 114,000 South Africans returned home
from foreign travel.
</P>
<P>
Statistics South Africa said that more citizens travelled
overseas and in Africa for holidays than for business.
</P>
<P>
Leading destinations were Britain, the United States, Zimbabwe
and Australia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
