on Belarus may still be ringing by mere inertia," Lukashenko said,
referring to negative assessments of some of the Belarussian
authorities' moves.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko said he would perceive them as "one-time
occurrences" that have nothing to do with the general policy
regarding Belarus, pursued by the European Union and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed Minsk's plans to establish good relations with
the West, saying that the statement on the wish to normalize
relations with the West is not "a courtesy to Europe or the United
States."
</P>
<P>
"Neither is it a spontaneous statement," Lukashenko said.
</P>
<P>
In another related development, U.S. Ambassador to Belarus
Daniel Speckhard welcomed Minsk's efforts to strengthen relations
with the United States and the West.
</P>
<P>
In a press release circulated in Minsk Thursday, Speckhard also
welcomed Lukashenko's plans to establish a dialogue with the
opposition and with the public in general, and his plans to hold
free and fair elections.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that the U.S. side welcomes the Belarussian
government's concrete work to establish a constructive dialogue
with the opposition, to lift limitations on the work of
independent media and nongovernmental organizations, and to free
ex-prime minister Mikhail Chigir and other people kept in prison
for political reasons, Interfax reported. 
</P>
