<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Central Bank Keeps Rate Unchanged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Central Bank (ECB) on
Thursday decided to keep its reference interest rates unchanged
despite the weak euro.
</P>
<P>
After a regular meeting at ECB's headquarters in Frankfurt, the
17-member executive council of the bank issued a short statement,
saying its two leading rates--marginal lending facility and
deposit facility--would stay at 2.5 percent and 1.5 percent
respectively.
</P>
<P>
But, the common central bank of 11 European nations indicated a
possible future switch in its rate policy.
</P>
<P>
Wim Duisenberg, chief of the ECB, said a tendency toward
tightening was entering the bank's guideline on monetary policy.
</P>
<P>
With the expectation that the euro-zone economy will pick up
the peace after a weak begin in year 1999, a re-assessment of
European monetary policy might be appropriate, if the currency and
credit growth continue to increase, said Duisenberg.
</P>
<P>
The ECB has not changed its leading interest rates since April,
when the bank lowered three main rates by a half percent. During
the following months, the euro kept dropping on international
money market to hit this week's new life-time low at 1.0124 U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The euro has lost some 15 percent of its value since it had
been launched this January. Many analysts said it would soon reach
parity with the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
Despite the recent negative performance of euro, Duisenberg
insisted the common European currency had "clear potential for a
stronger external value", a potential neglected by the financial
markets.
</P>
<P>
This was because the euro's value was firmly based on internal
price stability, stressed Duisenberg, expecting a further lower
inflation rate in the 11 eurolands despite the increasing energy
price.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
