<HEADLINE> U.N. Presence in Prevlaka to Extend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council on Thursday authorized the presence of U.N. military
observers for another six months in the Prevlaka peninsula
disputed by Croatia and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
In a resolution adopted unanimously, the council extended the
U.N. mandate until January 15 and called on the parties to resume
discussions for the solution of the dispute.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Mission of Observers in Prevlaka (UNMOP), consisting
of 27 military observers, has monitored the demilitarization of
the area since Croatia and Yugoslavia agreed to the U.N. presence
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The proposal to extend the observation was put forward by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan who said in his latest report that
the area patrolled by the observers had been relatively calm
during the recent months, except for the period of U.S.-British
air-strikes against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. military observers reported several violations by NATO
military aircraft, manned and unmanned, of the airspace over the
demilitarized zone the U.N. controlled zone in Prevlaka, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav air defense fired on those military aircraft while
"on several occasions, persons in civilian clothers, but
identified as military officers from NATO countries, entered the
U.N. controlled zone without authorization from UNMOP", the report
added.
</P>
<P>
The NATO action led Yugoslavia to postpone talks with Croatia
over the dispute, the report said. Four rounds of talks were held
from September 15, 1998 to March 9, 1999. Both parties have given
their assessment of the status of the negotiations following the
fourth round of talks.
</P>
<P>
Croatia declared independence from Yugoslavia in 1991, leaving
Prevlaka disputed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
