<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Cyber-Shopping Taken as Next Growth Wave </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Canada's National Economy, one of the
G7 generators, is seeing cyber-shopping as its next opportunity for
growth.
</P>
<P>
A record 688 million Canadian dollars (about 467.84 million U.S.
dollars) was reported to go to online vendors last year, yet only a
trifle of 0.28 percent of the total was netted within the country. The
rest? Said to move into the southern Uncle Sam, whose charisma is
believed to be ranging from a more of web-sites and commodities to a
low of price.
</P>
<P>
The contrast between quick growth and poor harvest makes the
country's economists anxious for improvement. The warning is that
anyone who neglects cyber-shopping as the next wave of business is
bound to be tramped.
</P>
<P>
To be more serious, the appeal sounds like a deadline within six
month, as if the country's business stall would certainly lose unless
something is done to check the trend.
</P>
<P>
The count is a balance of "three out of every five", meaning at
least 60 percent of Canadian cyber-spending would flow south in case
the cyber-system remains what it was in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Challenge to a change for the better is obvious: half of the
top 200 U.S. retailers against a quarter of 200 Canadian counterparts
-- in terms of availability of Internet shopping sites.
</P>
<P>
Yet the catch-up of the cyber-shopping business may be viewed
differently on the other hand. Canadian economists believe the country
has solid foundation for the on-line business explosion.
</P>
<P>
With an increasing number of Canadians embracing the debit card,
the economists even envisage a growth of 1,416 percent in E-commerce
revenues by 2003, when a cyber-income is estimated up to 80.4 billion
Canadian dollars (54.7 billion U.S. dollars), from the far more
insignificant 5.3 billion (about 3.6 billion U.S. dollars) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The pink idea beamed out of the data optimism, where about 10
million Canadians were counted as Internet users in 1998, while the
matter of course momentum could lead to a 23.9 million high out of the
then expected population of 32.5 million.
</P>
<P>
"Shopping on the Internet is clearly catching on with consumers,
and retailers need to keep pace," said the country's Retail Council
President Diane Brisebois at a recent meeting.
</P>
<P>
The president, like all others urging for an integrated
cyber-strategy for Canada, pointed to the significant opportunities to
expand business world wide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
