<HEADLINE> Security Council Lauds U.N. Kosovo Mission's Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Thursday voiced its appreciation of the effort by the U.N. Interim
Administration in Kosovo (UNMIK), which is in charge of ensuring
the law and order in the Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press, the president of the Security
Council, Hasimi Agam of Malaysia, said that "Members of the
Council welcomed the progress achieved in the implementation of
Security Council resolution 1244," adopted on June 10 in
endorsement of the U.N. Interim Administration Mission in Kosovo
(UNMIK) and international peacekeepers in Kosovo, known as KFOR.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Council expressed their appreciation for the
efforts being undertaken by UNMIK, including the advance work
accomplished by" U.N. Under-Secretary-General Sergio Vieira de
Mello, and his team, who arrived in Kosovo in mid-June.
</P>
<P>
De Mello is currently the acting head of the U.N. mission in
Kosovo, and Bernard Kouchner, the French health minister, is the
newly-appointed head of UNMIK. The latter arrived in Kosovo
Thursday, a U.N. spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Security Council Resolution 1244, UNMIK is designed
to ensure safety and security in the multi-ethnic Kosovo, and
undertake interim civil administration in the province until the
interim autonomous administration is elected.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Security Council members called on the
international community to "cooperate in ensuring the full
deployment of UNMIK and KFOR personnel as soon as possible," the
statement said. "They also appealed to all parties in Kosovo to
cooperate with UNMIK and KFOR."
</P>
<P>
The press statement echoed remarks by U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan, who is on an official visit to Slovakia. The U.N.
chief called on nations to do more to aid development in the
Balkans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
