<HEADLINE> ECB Begins Producing First Euro Banknotes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Central Bank (ECB) on
Thursday announced that it had begun printing banknotes of the
euro, the common European currency.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued after its executive council meeting in
Frankfurt, the ECB said first banknotes of the euro were being
produced in Germany, Belgium, the Netherlands, Italy, and Spain.
</P>
<P>
Six other eurolands, France, Austria, Luxemburg, Portugal,
Finnland and Ireland, soon will also begin printing euro
banknotes, said the ECB.
</P>
<P>
Totally 13 billion banknotes will be produced in the 11
countries that have merged their economy around the euro, and
nearly one third of the banknotes will be printed in German
federal printing house in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
Further 56 billion coins will be produced in the eurolands,
said the ECB, adding that 8 percent of them had been manufactured
before the end of this May.
</P>
<P>
The banknotes, par valued 600 billion euros, will go into
circulation on January 1, 2002, when 9 billion will be put into
market and 4 billion be reserved, the ECB said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
