<HEADLINE> Egyptian-Eritrean Cooperation Growing Steadily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 16 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian minister said on Friday
that the economic and trade cooperation between Egypt and Eritrea
"is growing steadily."
</P>
<P>
Minister of Trade and Supply Ahmed Gowaili made the remarks
before leaving here for Asmara to inaugurate the first ever fair
of Egyptian products in Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
The two countries, both members of the regional Common Market
of Eastern and Southern Africa, have sealed a number of agreements
on trade and economic cooperation, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Of the agreements, the most important one is that concerning
fishing, which is expected to prevent any future disputes between
the two countries in this respect, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian minister, leading a delegation of officials and
businessmen, is to open on Saturday a week-long fair, which falls
within Egypt's policy to open new markets for its products, the
country's Middle East News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The fair will display construction material, ceramics,
medicines, chemicals, foodstuffs, ovens, TV sets, auto spare
parts and electronics, the news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Eritrean Ambassador in Cairo Mohamed Omar said on Friday that
the two countries are considering formation of a joint committee
of foreign ministers in a bid to boost cooperation, especially in
the private sector.
</P>
<P>
Omar called for the opening of maritime lines to link the two
countries in addition to the existing air routes as transport has
become the main obstacle to the growth of bilateral trade.
</P>
<P>
The trade volume between Egypt and Eritrea stood at 98 million
Egyptian pounds (28.82 million U.S. dollars) last year. Medicine
was the main goods Eritrea imported from Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
