<HEADLINE> Stone-Age Cave Unearthed in Southern Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian and Belgian archaeologists
have unearthed a cave that dates back to 7000 B.C. near an ancient
Red Sea port, a senior official said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Granite axes, knives and hunting tools were found in the
Neolithic-era cave 40 kilometers west of al-Qoseir, said Mohammed
el-Saghir, head of the Egyptian Archaeology Department. However,
he did not specify when the cave was found.
</P>
<P>
Primitive paintings marked the walls, el-Saghir said.
</P>
<P>
"The cave seems to be rich with important evidence of human
life during the stone age," he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Another cave found 500 meters away is expected to yield similar
results, el-Saghir said.
</P>
<P>
Until the 10th century, al-Qoseir, 500 kilometers southeast of
Cairo, was the most important port on the Red Sea coast. Egypt is
now planning a major resort in the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
