<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Report Says Poverty Still Blights Human Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Poverty continues to blight the
lives of people worldwide, including people in the United States
and other developed nations, according to a report released this
week by the United Nations Development Program (UNDP).
</P>
<P>
When judged by the Human Development Index (HDI), which
combines average life expectancy, education, and income, the lives
of people around the world improved from 1975 to 1999, the report
said, but poverty is still pervasive in many countries like Benin,
Nepal, and Niger.
</P>
<P>
But it is not confined to developing countries. In Denmark,
average life expectancy is 76 years, but 13 percent of the
population do not reach the age of 60. In Ireland, 23 percent of
the people are functionally illiterate, and in the United States,
nearly 20 percent of the people have incomes below the national
poverty line.
</P>
<P>
More alarmingly, in the 1990s, reverse human development has
been recorded in 16 countries, largely because of the impact of
HIV/AIDS in southern and eastern Africa and economic stagnation in
sub-Saharan Africa, Eastern Europe, and the countries of the
former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
The top five on the list of countries and regions according to
HDI are Canada, Norway, the United States, Japan and Belgium.
China's Hong Kong Special Administrative Region ranked 24th while
China ranked 98th.
</P>
<P>
The report emphasized that countries do not need unlimited
income to have respectable levels of human development. Socially
sensitive policymaking, instead, is the key factor. Richard Jolly,
the principal coordinator of the report, was quoted as saying that
income is not the sum total of human lives, and that of human
development is deeper and richer than that.
</P>
<P>
Income is only a means to human development, not an end in
itself, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Report Says Internet Widening Gap Among Human Beings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The worldwide computer link-up,
the Internet, is helping widen the global gap between the haves
and have-nots and the knows and the know-nots, according to this
year's version of the United Nations Development Program report
that appeared this week.
</P>
<P>
The report has been published annually since 1990. This year's
report says that the gap is widening because access to the
Internet differs widely. The United States, for example, has more
computers than the rest of the world combined, and Bulgaria has
more Internet users than the whole of sub-Saharan Africa,
excluding South Africa. South Asia, with 23 percent of the world's
population, has less than one percent of the world's Internet
users.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere, the Internet divides the literate from the
illiterate (60 percent of the users in China have a university
degree), men from women (in Brazil, 75 percent of the users are
men), rich from poor (a computer costs the average Bangladeshi
more than eight years of salary, compared with a month's wages for
the average American), young from old (the average British user is
under 30), and urban from rural, the report says.
</P>
<P>
The typical Internet user worldwide is male, below the age of
35, has a university education and high income, is urban based and
English speaking, in other words, the member of a very elite
minority, it says.
</P>
<P>
While the rich countries take advantage of the Internet's
information to help develop their technology and economies, the
needs and concerns of poor countries and poor people, who have
been denied access almost imperceptibly are being left out of the
global conversation, it says.
</P>
<P>
One way to solve this problem the report suggests is to collect
a "bit tax" on data transmitted via the Internet. A tax of one U.S.
cent on every 100 lengthy e-mails would generate well over 70
billion U.S. dollars a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
