<HEADLINE> EU, China to Start Negotiation on Maritime Transport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) and China
are to start negotiations on a bilateral maritime transport
agreement, the European Commission said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive body described the talks as a breakthrough in
its transport relations with China in a statement, saying that "
The two sides have been trying to reach agreement on the basis for
negotiations for over a year".
</P>
<P>
The Commission said the first technical meeting is expected to
take place before the end of the year in order to clarify scope
and issues for a bilateral agreement.
</P>
<P>
The EU and China, the two regional influential powers, also
agreed to work for setting up possible cooperation in other areas.
</P>
<P>
EU acting commissioner for transport policy Neil Kinnock said:
"This agreement is evidence of the improved maritime relations
between the EU and China over the last few years and reflects the
fact that we have an overriding common interest in efficient
transport links and open markets."
</P>
<P>
"I am pleased we have taken this step forward," the vice-
president designate of the next five-year term European Commission
said in his written statement. 
</P>
