<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Geraniums Prove Pollution Eating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Canadian researchers have found
that lemon-scented geraniums can be used to restore a toxic land
patch to a "Garden of Eden", reported "the Globe and Mail" Friday.
</P>
<P>
The familiar flowering plant has an uncanny ability to absorb
metal and organic pollutants which could help detoxify everything
from abandoned gas station sites to old mining lands, the daily
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The geraniums can soak up as much as 3,300 milligrams (mgs) of
Cadmium, 18,700 mgs of lead, 6,400 mgs of nickel and 650 mgs of
copper for every kilogram of plant tissue in two weeks, without
exhibiting any sign of toxic stress.
</P>
<P>
The researchers come to the conclusion after planting the lemon-
scented geraniums in contaminated soil samples in Canada. The
result is that by planting geraniums, the contaminated soil could
be used for farming.
</P>
<P>
This is in sharp contrast with other methods to get rid of
toxic metals in the soil, which can thus be cleaned but left
useless.
</P>
<P>
Metals are a key enemy of plant growth and result in stunted
plants and poor harvests in southeastern United States, Central
and South America, North Africa and parts of India and China, the
newspaper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
