<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's insurance companies have been given three
months to raise their capital to 1.5 million U.S. dollars from the
current 200,000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
Nasser Saidi, Minister of Economy, Trade and Industry, said
in a circular that the count-down starts from July 28.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe that half of Lebanon's 80 insurance companies
may either go bankrupt or sell their portfolios to bigger firms.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's officials said the move was aimed at
streamlining the country's insurance market.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel is due to visit
Egypt on July 26, accompanied by a delegation of 50 Turkish
businessmen, in an effort to boost bilateral ties in the fields of
contractor activities, construction and tourism.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports quoted President of the Egyptian
Businessmen Association Saeed Tawil as saying that Demirel will
chair on his second day in Egypt a joint conference of Egyptian
and Turkish businessmen, which will also be attended by a number
of officials.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will examine the prospects of economic, trade and
investment cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- A round-table meeting of Egyptian and British
businessmen is due to be held in London on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Egypt will send a 30-member delegation to the meeting, to be
led by President of the Egyptian Businessmen Association Saeed
Tawil, the Arab daily "Al Hayat" reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will discuss the issue of investment in Egypt's
Egyptian stock markets and giant projects.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- Saudi Arabia's share market witnessed over the
past week a rise in the number and value of circulating shares,
and a decline in the number of effected transactions.
</P>
<P>
Circulating shares have been subjected to sales operations in
pursuit of definite profits, as a result of the continuing rise in
market price throughout the past two weeks, the Arab daily "Al
Hayat" reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
In turn, this development led to some decline in price, though
the market soon overcame that, by virtue of the continuing
improvement in oil prices and by the positive results attained by
most circulating companies during the first half of the current
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
