<HEADLINE> Sharif Warns India Not to Take Peace Efforts as Weakness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif Friday said that Pakistan firmly believes in peaceful
resolution of issues, but warned India not to wrongly construe its
peace efforts as a sign of weakness.
</P>
<P>
Addressing troops in the Shiok valley, near Line of Control in
Kashmir, Sharif said, "It must be kept in mind that Pakistan ...
is fully capable of defending its territorial integrity. In the
wake of any aggression, we are capable of giving a befitting
reply."
</P>
<P>
Sharif earlier this month managed to make the freedom fighters
begin withdrawing from Kargil where they had been fighting against
the Indian troops for two months, and thus extinguished the fuse
to a possible fourth Indo-Pak war in time.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said that Pakistan has been able to avert a
catastrophic war, which could have brought vast-scale destruction
and devastation.
</P>
<P>
"I have repeatedly stated that it is easier to start a
conflagration, while it is difficult to remain steadfast to the
commitment of no-war," he said, quoted by the Associated Press of
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
In the past, he stated, Pakistan had been thrust into three
wars with India and "in all these wars, both countries lost
immensely, and gained nothing."
</P>
<P>
Sharif, however, stressed that Pakistanis remain fully alert to
the defense of their motherland.
</P>
<P>
"Hence, once again, I want to tell any adventurer that our
endeavors for peace must never be construed as a sign of weakness.
We are fully capable of confronting and surmounting any
challenge," he asserted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
