<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Executes Two Foreign Drug Smugglers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia on Friday
executed two foreign drug smugglers, bringing to 29 the number of
those beheaded on drug crimes this year in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi Press Agency quoted an Interior Ministry statement
as saying that Saudi religious courts had sentenced to death a
Nigerian woman named Aisha Saada Qassem and Habib Qal Mohammad, an
Afghan, both convicted of smuggling cocaine and heroine in the
country.
</P>
<P>
With the executions, the agency said, the Gulf Arab country
has in this year beheaded 29 Saudi and foreign drug smugglers.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, like other oil-rich Gulf countries, is becoming
one of the clear targets of drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
Riyadh considers drug-related crimes as destructive to the
society and imposes capital punishment against drug traffickers
and dealers. 
</P>
