<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Introduce ECOWAS Travellers Cheque </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Minister of Finance Mallam
Adamu Ciroma is scheduled to launch and introduce into immediate
circulation the Economic Community for West African States
(ECOWAS) Travellers Cheque in capital Abuja on July 22.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman of the Central Bank of Nigeria, Tony Ede, said in a
press release Thursday that Nigeria would on that date join 10
other ECOWAS members in issuing and accepting ECOWAS Travellers
Cheque (ETC) as a medium of transaction in the west African
region.
</P>
<P>
The travellers cheque is denominated in five, 10, 20, 50 and
100 West African Unit of Account which is pegged to the Special
Drawing Rights of the International Monetary Fund and is currently
valued at 1.36 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The rate of conversion, the release said, will be published
weekly while the ECOWAS cheque is expected to be used for the
payment of goods and services within the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
The idea of introducing a west African travellers cheque was
first muted in early 1987 when the ECOWAS heads of state and
government adopted a Monetary Cooperation Program.
</P>
<P>
At that ECOWAS summit, the heads of state and government
approved the introduction of a sub-regional payment instrument to
facilitate inter- regional trade, tourism and cross-border
transactions as one of the short- term objectives of the monetary
cooperation program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
