<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Privatizes 170 State-Owned Enterprises in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Some 170 state-owned
enterprises have been privatized in Ethiopia since the 1995/96
fiscal year, the Ethiopian News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Of all enterprises privatized so far, most of the small ones
have been sold to domestic investors, while a number of larger
ones have been acquired by foreign investors, an Ethiopian
investment guide document indicated.
</P>
<P>
The privatized enterprises include a gold mine, soft drinks
companies, a brewery, meat processing and canning plants and a
tannery.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian government led by Prime Minister Meles Zenawi
initiated a privatization program in 1995/96.
</P>
<P>
In the coming three years, the government plans to further
privatize 120 enterprises and units.
</P>
<P>
"Most of these enterprises are large, and the government is
keen to encourage further participation by foreign investors in
the privatization program," the document said.
</P>
<P>
State-owned big hotels, textiles, pharmaceuticals, food
complexes, beverage factories, construction companies and food
factories are among the lists of enterprises and units to be
privatized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
