<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Economy Slows Down (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Statistics show that in the first half this year, retail
commodities prices fell by 3.2 percent from a year earlier, while
per capita income of urban residents grew by only 5.9 percent. The
income of rural residents grew at an even slower rate of 2.1
percent for the period, lagging 5.5 percentage points behind the
country's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Ye said that ebbing demand has become an obvious economic
problem reflected in the lack of investment interest in the non-
state sector, lackluster consumption, and decreasing exports and
foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
Investment in fixed assets by the non-state sector grew by only
5.7 percent in the first half, far below the national average
growth rate of 15.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Exports in the past six months had a year-on-year fall of 4.6
percent to 8.3 billion U.S. dollars, reducing China's trade
surplus to eight billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Actual foreign direct investment totaled 18.6 billion U.S.
dollars in the January-June period, decreasing 9.2 percent over
the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
However, Ye emphasized, the 7.6-percent growth rate in the
first half is still among the highest in the world. Noting that
the first-half year saw all-round improvement in the industrial
structure and profitability in state-owned enterprises, he said
that the country is confident of achieving this year's economic
growth target.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Economy Slows Down (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- China's economic growth slowed in
the first-half of the year but the annual target still can be
achieved, a spokesman for the National Bureau of Statistics said
here today.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Ye Zhen told a press conference that the economic
growth rate was estimated at 7.1 percent year-on-year for the
second quarter, 1.2 percentage points lower than for the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted, the economic growth rate for the first-half
of the year was 7.6 percent and the annual growth target of seven
percent can be achieved.
</P>
<P>
He said that the economic slowdown of the past six months was
due to a slump in the growth of industrial production, sluggish
sales, and slow agricultural growth.
</P>
<P>
Industrial output grew by nine percent on an year-on-year basis
in the second quarter, 1.1 percentage points lower than that of
the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
Sales of retail goods grew by only 6.4 percent year-on-year to
147.53 billion yuan in the first half of the year, which was 1.2
percentages points lower than the economic growth rate.
</P>
<P>
Deflation became increasingly apparent in the January-June
period this year, with retail prices continuing to fall and
personal income growing slowly, Ye said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
