<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congo(K) Main Rebel Group Turns Down Kabila's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Congolese Rally for Democracy
(RCD), main rebel group in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC),
has turned down a general amnesty offered early this week by
President Laurent Kabila, saying that Kabila's removal from power
remained its primary objective.
</P>
<P>
"I think Kabila is the one who deserves (to be offered) amnesty
in the first place. We are not criminals to seek amnesty," the
Rwanda News Agency Friday quoted Moise Nyarugabo, vice-president
of the rebel movement, as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Kabila should seek forgiveness from the rebels and all
Congolese people.
</P>
<P>
The only way to do so is to quit power and leave the Congolese
in peace,"

Nyarugabo said late Thursday. "We do not need to be forgiven by
him."
</P>
<P>
The rebel leader denied that his movement was responsible for
some of those deaths, saying that his fighters had killed only
Kabila's soldiers on the battle front.
</P>
<P>
Nyarugabo rejected claims by Kabila and his allies that rebels
had launched attacks on several fronts in the northeast and
southeast of the vast central African country.
</P>
<P>
"Kabila and his allies proceeded on a well-known method of
making accusations because that is the best attack," Nyarugabo
said.
</P>
<P>
Kabila and the leaders of five other African nations who have
sent troops to fight on either side of the war signed a cease-fire
deal in Zambian capital Lusaka last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Nyarugabo said that soon after the cease-fire was signed,
Kabila's troops launched attacks on the rebel-held towns of
Gbadolite, Ikela and Kamitunga in the Equator and eastern regions
of the DRC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
