<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN's Future to Be Basic Issue at Ministerial Meeting: Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers from the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) will discuss the
regional grouping's future in next week's ministerial meeting, a
Singapore Foreign Ministry spokesman said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman told a press conference that no fixed agenda is
arranged for the 32nd ASEAN Ministerial Meeting (AMM), but the
basic issue is ASEAN's future.
</P>
<P>
He said the ministers can be expected to examine fundamental
functions to see whether they need to be modified in light of new
developments.
</P>
<P>
For the first time, the foreign ministers will meet without the
presence of other officials to discuss among themselves very
candidly and realistically long-term issues and challenges facing
ASEAN, said the spokesman whose country is chairing the meeting.
</P>
<P>
There are anxieties about ASEAN's future, understandably so
since its largest member Indonesia is preoccupied with internal
problems and the Asian crisis has badly damaged the ASEAN's
reputation and taken some of the gloss off its image, he said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN's expansion with new members at different levels of
economic and political development has also made decision-making
slower, he said.
</P>
<P>
"ASEAN is currently in the phase of consolidation," he said.
"We tend to use the AMM meeting to send a signal that ASEAN as a
regional grouping is still nonetheless confident of its future."
</P>
<P>
The 6th ASEAN Regional Forum (ARF), due to begin after the
ministerial meeting, will discuss issues in two broad areas --
regional and international issues, he said.
</P>
<P>
The ARF meeting will focus on "security implications of the
regional crisis, security challenges in the region, transnational
issues with security implications and most importantly the future
of ARF," he said.
</P>
<P>
As for the Post Ministerial Conferences (PMC) which involves
ASEAN's ten dialogue countries, the focus will be on non-security
transnational issues, he said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN members will examine the future of PMC in consultation
with dialogue partners, he added.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN now groups Brunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Malaysia,
Myanmar, Laos, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
