<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawsuit from American Company on Sydney Olympic Bands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- An American company is suing the
Sydney Olympic Games organizers for breach of contract for not
using their bands on the opening ceremony of the Games.
</P>
<P>
Under pressure of a local outcry, the Sydney Olympics
Organizing Committee (SOCOG) changed its mind last month to use
local musicians, instead of recruiting 1,500 U.S. and Japanese
college students to march at the opening.
</P>
<P>
The public forced SOCOG to drop plans to get bands from World
Projects Corp, who had contracted with SOCOG to organize marching
bands.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, the U.S. company filed a writ in the New South Wales
state supreme court suing SOCOG and its president Michael Knight.
</P>
<P>
Knight said the court action was provocative and would be
vigorously fought. 
</P>
