<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Further Promote Pro-active Financial Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Localities and relevant
departments across China are urged to take immediate steps and
increase efforts to implement the government's pro-active
financial policy in a move to expand domestic demand.
</P>
<P>
The call came at a meeting held here today by the State
Development Planning Commission and the Ministry of Finance, a day
after the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China and
the State Council decided to adopt a more active financial policy
to spur the economy.
</P>
<P>
These measures are necessary and feasible to stimulate domestic
demand and guide and attract investment from all social sectors to
sustain rapid and healthy economic growth, meeting participants
said.
</P>
<P>
Investment priorities should be focused on both short-term
projects for immediate economic growth and long-term projects that
will help lay a solid foundation for long-range social and
economic progress, the two ministries said.
</P>
<P>
The emphasis should be placed on major industries and the
overall economic growth as well, in order to improve economic
restructuring and people's lives while preventing redundant
projects, the two departments said.
</P>
<P>
Increased investment should first go to projects already under
construction, technological upgrading projects, high-tech
industrialization, projects that can attract loans and social
investment, the central and western areas, and social development
projects such as university students housing and village radio and
television networks.
</P>
<P>
The two ministries also called for strict project supervision,
good quality, and proper use of project funds.
</P>
<P>
China issued an additional 100 billion yuan worth of treasury
bonds last year to ameliorate the negative effects of the Asian
financial crisis on domestic demand. A year's experience has
demonstrated that this policy is correct, contributing an
estimated 1.5 percentage points to the country's gross domestic
product growth.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
