<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 11:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sudan Reserves Over U.S. Envoy for South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese Minister of Foreign
Affairs Mustafa Osman Ismail has described the U.S. decision to
appoint a special envoy for the war in south Sudan as "a step
worthy of consideration and evaluation."
</P>
<P>
But Ismail said that it is premature to term the decision
"positive or negative."
</P>
<P>
Ismail said the Sudanese government had not received any
official information from the U.S. administration regarding the
decision, Sudanese daily Al Rai Al Am reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ismail also said Sudan's response would be based on the
Sudanese government's approval of the principle of dialog, its
endeavour to normalize ties with the U.S., and Khartoum's interest
in promoting a positive U.S. role in Sudanese issues, particularly
the establishment of peace in south Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Ismail pointed out that Sudan will continue to cherish dialog
with the U.S. in order to treat and normalize bilateral relations,
paving way for a positive role for the U.S. in such issues as
peace and relief work.
</P>
<P>
He said the Sudan would examine the U.S. decision, its
objectives and affiliation of the envoy.
</P>
<P>
Ismail pointed out some members in the U.S. government harbor
hostility towards Sudan and a neutral envoy is preferred.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted that Ismail's statement constitutes the
first official Sudanese reaction to the U.S. presidential decree
to appoint an American envoy to deal with the war in south Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, certain Sudanese political sources have warned that
the appointment means placing Sudan, south and north alike, under
trusteeship, and the restoration of the era of the British High
Commissioner under British colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out that welcoming an American envoy was, in
effect, submitting to the design of U.S. Secretary of State
Madaleine Albright aimed at gaining control over Sudan.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old civil war between Sudanese government and
southern rebels have ravaged the country and more than 1.5 million
people have died as a result of the fighting and famines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
