<HEADLINE> U.N. Team, Iraq Agree on Removing Chemical Agents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The visiting U.N. technical team,
which is entrusted to remove toxic chemical agents left behind by
U.N. arms inspectors, and Iraq have agreed on the process of
carrying out the mission.
</P>
<P>
The process of removing quantities of chemical agents and
mustard gas samples has been decided at a meeting held on Thursday
between the Iraqi side led by presidential adviser Amer as-Saadi
and the U.N. team led by South African Dirk van Niekerk, the Iraqi
News Agency reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report said the real work of destroying these chemical
agents and mustard gas samples left behind by the U.N. Special
Commission (UNSCOM) on disarming Iraq would start Friday, but it
did not reveal how and where the work will be done.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. team, which comprises four chemical experts from the
Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons in the Hague
and an independent biological weapons expert, arrived in Baghdad
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
These U.N. experts are from China, Russia, Poland and
Germany. Yako Yalato, a Finnish, former assistant director of
U.N. Baghdad Monitoring and Verification Center, acts as guide for
the U.N. team.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and the U.N. reached an agreement last month on the
composition of the technical team to close UNSCOM's Baghdad
laboratory where one kilogram of mustard gas and VX gas were left
behind before the commission withdrew from Iraq last December.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM has not resumed its work of weapons inspections in
Iraq since last December when the United States and Britain
launched four-night airstrikes against Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
