<HEADLINE> China's Securities Investment Funds Disclose Assets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- China's 10 new securities
investment funds today disclosed their portfolio as of June 30.
</P>
<P>
Yuyang Fund announced a net asset value of 1.72 yuan per share,
topping all others, followed by Anxin Fund at 1.65 yuan.
</P>
<P>
The Taihe Fund and the Jintai Fund reported the lowest net
assets, with shares valued at 1.19 yuan and 1.37 yuan,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
All 10 funds were formed after promulgation by the State
Council of the Temporary Regulations on the Administration of
Securities Investment Funds on November 14, 1997, they are,
therefore, known in China as the new funds, to distinguish them
from the funds formed before then.
</P>
<P>
Investment in stocks generally accounted for about 78 percent
of the new funds' total net asset value, but for the Jinghong and
Hansheng funds, the percentage is as high as 93 percent and 88
percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
For all the 10 funds, electronics and telecommunications stocks
are the first choice, and investment in these industries account
for as high as 40 percent of Yuyang Fund's net asset value.
</P>
<P>
Other sectors invested in heavily by the funds include
transportation, electricity, automobiles, machinery, petroleum
chemicals, and consumer electronics.
</P>
<P>
China now has 14 new securities investment funds. The latest
two, the Pufeng and Xinghe funds, have yet to be listed on the
Shanghai and Shenzhen exchanges.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
