<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambican Govt. Strives for Social Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Mozambican government has made
great efforts to accelerate the social development of the poor
southern African country.
</P>
<P>
Due to the economic restructuring, high adult illiteracy and
fast population growth, more than 60 percent of Mozambicans are
unemployed or semi-unemployed, the Mozambican government said in
its report on the national social development to be submitted to
the United Nations later this month.
</P>
<P>
However, the government has helped train some 15,000
job-seekers through various training programs and has invested
large amount of fund in the educational and vocational training
institutions in the past five year.
</P>
<P>
The report carried in Friday's Noticias newspaper noted that
during 1995 and 1999, the government has granted loans to some
8,000 people and offered tools to some 10,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican government has helped establish 281 companies,
creating some 11,000 jobs in such sectors as agriculture, civil
engineering and bakery while in the same period creating some
50,000 temporary jobs in the rehabilitation and building of such
infrastructures as roads.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, in the four years, some 245,000
Mozambicans were legally employed in South Africa with the help
from he Mozambican government.
</P>
<P>
However, the report pointed out that Mozambique is still one of
the poorest countries in the world, with per capita income of its
15.5-million population (in 1997 census) is merely 100 U.S.
dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
Some 39.5 percent of the illerate adult population became
literate during the past four years, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
