<HEADLINE> Share Prices Fall in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed lower in Tokyo
Friday on profit-taking after the key Nikkei index briefly topped
18,500 for the first time in 22 months.
</P>
<P>
The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average on the First Section of the
Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 183.56 points, or 1.00 percent, from
Thursday's close to end at 18,248.30, after hitting 18,623.15.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, edged down 4.71 points or 0.31 percent to 1,
507.02.
</P>
<P>
Continued rises in high-priced blue chips boosted the key index
in the morning session, but they faced strong selling in the
afternoon and led the index into the minus territory, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Arbitrage-linked selling, stirred by a decline in index futures
prices, also weighed on overall share prices, they said.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section expanded to 943.68 million shares
from 765.18 million shares Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Itochu Corp. was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers exceeded
gainers 779 to 417, with 133 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
