<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Human Development Challenges Pressing: U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Human Development Report
1999 of the United Nations has ranked Pakistan the 138th among 174
countries and regions on the basis of the Human Development Index
(HDI).
</P>
<P>
The report was launched across the world, including Pakistan,
Harumi Sukaguchi, resident representative of the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) in Pakistan, Friday released the report
at a ceremony at the United Nations Information Center in
Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
The report ranked Pakistan among the group of countries
categorized as Medium Human Development. Compared with the 1998
report, Pakistan has graduated from the Low Human Development
countries and regions to the Medium Human Development countries
and regions.
</P>
<P>
"In fact this change for good has occurred not because of some
breakthrough on the human development scene of the country, but
this has occurred because of methodological changes in the HDI
calculations," the report said.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that Pakistan's human development challenges
remain pressing.
</P>
<P>
The 1999 report has placed the 174 countries and regions in
three categories based on the comprehensive evaluation of per
capita income, poverty deprivation, literacy rate, life
expectancy, gender equality, and so on.
</P>
<P>
The three categories are High Human Development, Medium Human
Development and Low Human Development, with 45, 94 and 35
countries and regions separately in the first, second and third
categories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Inflation Rate Doubles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's inflation rate doubled
from 6.1 percent in May 1998 to an estimated 12.2 percent in May
this year and may rise further in the next several months,
according to Joseph Sanusi, governor of the Central Bank of
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a monthly luncheon of the Nigerian Economic Summit
Group on Thursday, the governor noted that the risk of further
acceleration of the inflation rate is high as the current rate had
not reflected the "lagged effect of the excessive government
spending".
</P>
<P>
Due to the "lackluster attitude of government since 1998", he
said, the federal government of Nigeria recorded an estimated
205.7 billion Naira (about 2.057 billion U.S. Dollars) deficit in
the first five months this year, The Post Express reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The amount of the five-month deficit is 3.7 billion Naira
(about 37 million Dollars) above the 202 billion Naira (about 2.02
billion Dollars) projected for the whole year of 1999, Sanusi
said.
</P>
<P>
As the demand for foreign exchange remained at an unsustained
level, he noted, official external reserves position plunged from
7.1 billion Dollars at the end of December 1998 to 4.6 billion
Dollars at the end of June 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to him, this is "an amount that could barely meet the
 conventionally accepted external reserve adequacy level of three
months of imports."
</P>
<P>
The governor pointed out that an estimated output growth rate
for the first half of 1999 was 1.1 percent while the unemployment
rate remained unacceptably high.
</P>
<P>
Though most of these problems are not our own making, he noted,
the Central Bank of Nigeria would accept the challenge of dealing
effectively with these problems in order to ensure the
re-establishment of a stable macro-economic environment.
</P>
<P>
The apex bank has embarked on monetary policy actions including
the issue of the Special Treasury Bills, upward review of both the
Cash Reserve Ratio and Liquidity Ratio from 8 to 12 percent and 30
to 40 percent respectively, according to him.
</P>
<P>
Sanusi said these measures are painful but they are necessary
given the need to restore a stable macro-economic environment
which is a prerequisite for sustainable growth and the external
viability of the economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
