<HEADLINE> Candidates' Performance Declining in Nigeria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The general performance of
candidates for this year's university matriculation examination is
poor compared with last year, according to the Joint Admissions
and Matriculation Board (JAMB).
</P>
<P>
Board Registrar Bellow Salim made the revelation in capital
Abuja Thursday when he announced the results of the 1999
examinations, This Day newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
At a press briefing, he said that the mean scores in Geography,
Biology, Chemistry and Mathematics showed a decline in candidates'
performance, compared with the 1998 results.
</P>
<P>
For instance, the mean score for mathematics was 38.90 as
against last year's 53.50, said the registrar, adding that there
had been a noticeable decline in the quality of performance in
science subjects over the years.
</P>
<P>
"In view of this lapse and our urgent manpower need in the
sciences, efforts should be seriously intensified to improve upon
the teaching of these subjects at the secondary school level,"
Salim stressed.
</P>
<P>
According to him, a total of 400,194 out of 417,773 candidates
actually sat for the examination while 17,579 did not turn up for
the examination at their various centers across the country.
</P>
<P>
The registrar noted that there was a boost in women's quest for
 university education as a total of 175,897 female candidates sat
for the examination, accounting for 44 percent of the total
applicants.
</P>
<P>
As 8,073 candidates were involved in examination malpractice
this year, the results of the candidates who represented 2.01
percent of the total number of applicants, had been withheld, he
said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the generally low incidence of irregularities and
 malpractice recorded during the examination could be attributed
to some measures put in place by JAMB, including the innovation
in which questions were joggled and segmented into "different
types". 
</P>
</TEXT>
