<HEADLINE> China's Airlines Increase Domestic, International Flights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- China's airlines recently
increased a number of domestic and international flights to meet
the needs of the summer travel season.
</P>
<P>
 Air China, one of the biggest airlines in the country, has
decided to use Boeing 747 and Boeing 777 planes to replace the
Boeing 767 on daily Beijing-Seoul flights.
</P>
<P>
 In addition, the airlines will add 12 temporary flights on
the Beijing-Fusan route during July 17-August 14.
</P>
<P>
 They also plan to increase flights from Beijing to Yanji, a
tourist city on the border between China and the Democratic People
's Republic of Korea, from one a day to three.
</P>
<P>
 Southern China Airlines expects to increase flights from
Changsha, capital of central China's Hunan Province, to Hong Kong,
to six a week.
</P>
<P>
 And Hainan Airlines has inaugurated three flights a week from
Haikou, capital of Hainan Province, via Changsha to Qingdao, a
coastal tourist city in east China's Shandong Province.  
</P>
