<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Launch New Fight Against Superstition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scholars in both the
natural and social sciences today launched a new campaign against
superstition, which has been surging in China recently.
</P>
<P>
Superstitions lately emerging in China includes the belief in
ghosts, witchcraft, and supernatural abilities in the disguise of
science and traditional culture, said Ren Jiyu, president of the
China Atheism Society.
</P>
<P>
Ren said at a forum against superstition and pseudo-science
sponsored by the China Association for Science and Technology (
CAST) that superstitious activities are disturbing social
stability and development.
</P>
<P>
A survey conducted by CAST last year showed that 35.5 percent
of Chinese citizens believe in fortune-telling and divination, a
figure nearly seven percentage points higher than the 28.7 percent
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Experts attending today's forum shared the opinion that China
should increase people's scientific awareness and ban the
publication of books and magazines disseminating superstition.
Those who make money by telling fortunes should be punished
according to the law, they opined.
</P>
<P>
A new journal, Science and Atheism, sponsored by the China
Atheism Society, began publication today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
