<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Probe Efficacy of New AIDS Drug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 16 (Xinhua) -- South African Health Minister
Manto Tshbalala-Msimang plans to lead a delegation to Uganda to
investigate the efficacy of a new drug which reportedly reduces
mother-to-child transmission of HIV/AIDS, 702 Radio reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The drug, Nevirapine, was jointly developed by the United
States and Ugandan researchers.
</P>
<P>
Tshabalala-Msimang was considering introducing the drug to
South Africa, according to the radio report.
</P>
<P>
The health minister appeared optimistic that the
anti-retroviral drug could be a cost-effective way of reducing the
high incidence of AIDS among infants in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"If indeed it does stop transmission from mother to child, it
will be a breakthrough," Tshabalala-Msimang was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
She said her ministry wanted to be satisfied that the drug was
as effective as claimed by the American and Uganda researchers.
</P>
<P>
"All that remains is for us to get more information and then we
will take appropriate steps."
</P>
<P>
Studies on Nevirapine at Uganda's Mulago Hospital over an
18-month period, discovered that a double oral dose of the
anti-retroviral drug Nevirapine given to an HIV-infected mother in
labor, and to her baby at birth, reduces the risk of transmission
to the unborn child by up to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
Between 25 and 30 percent of infected pregnant mothers usually
pass on the HIV virus, which leads to AIDS to their children,
according to Ugandan figures.
</P>
<P>
Nevirapine, which is manufactured by Germany pharmaceutical
company, Boehringer-Ingelheim, costs around 25 rand (about four
U.S. dollars) per treatment, making it significantly cheaper than
drugs currently on the market.
</P>
<P>
Tshabalala-Msimang's predecessor Nkosazana Zuma was widely
criticized for refusing to give the anti-AIDS drug, AZT, to
pregnant HIV-positive women at state hospitals. Zuma had insisted
that the government could not afford to dispense the drug.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Protect Plant Genetic Resources: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Plant genetic resources is of
great importance in the national development while all biological
resources will continue to be of concern to all the society,
Kenyan Environment Minister Francis Nyenze has said.
</P>
<P>
To safeguard genetic resources, the country's plant genetic
resources regulation will be tabled for discussion in Parliament
and the bill will surely go through, the minister said at a
three-day workshop on intellectual property right and protection
of plant genetic resources in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Nyenze noted that it was absolutely essential that
bio-diversity issues are accorded their rightful place in the
national development as industrialization has placed them on the
forefront.
</P>
<P>
It also needs to regulate the access to and the sharing of
benefits from the use of the genetic resources, local media Friday
quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
G. Thitai, an expert from the Genetic Resources Expert Working
Group told the workshop that at least 18,000 species of rare
plants including coffee, barley, parsley and various fruits and
vegetables had been smuggled out of Kenya by prospectors since
1987.
</P>
<P>
"Access to genetic resources outside the protected areas has
taken place easily without local benefitting and must now stop,"
Thitai said.
</P>
<P>
The participants at the workshop urged African countries to
develop laws governing commercial use of genetic resources to
ensure they benefit from bio-technology.
</P>
<P>
About 150 participants from local institutions, U.N. agencies,
Uganda, Tanzania and Malawi attended the workshop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0169 </DOCNO>
