<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Photos Show Java Rhinoceros Survives in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Photos of Java rhinoceros released
by Vietnam's Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development (MARD),
the Dutch Embassy in Vietnam and the Would Wildlife Fund (WWF)
prove that the precious animal has survived in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The photos of the single-horned rhinoceros (or rhinoceros
sondaicus annamiticus) were released for the first time at a press
briefing in Hanoi on Thursday, Vietnam's official news agency VNA
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
A total of seven pictures showing this rare animal in four
different positions were taken by automatic cameras during May 11
and 25 at locations in the Cat Tien National Park in southern
Vietnam, 150 kilometers north of Ho Chi Minh City.
</P>
<P>
One photo shows a rhino with a small horn -- a characteristic
of female Javan rhinos. Another photo shows a rhino with an open
mouth and large incisors - a characteristic of male Javan rhinos.
</P>
<P>
"This is one of the most exciting events in the natural history
of Vietnam, and this exercise may even prove that there are more
than eight rhinos surviving in the area," said Tran Van Mui,
director of the park.
</P>
<P>
The photo-trapping project is part of the 6-million-U.S.-dollar
WWF-Cat Tien National Park Conservation Project funded by the
governments of Vietnam and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
Cat Tien park, covering an area of about 75,000 hectares,
includes a rhino sanctuary, which was created by the Vietnamese
government in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The Cat Tien National Park is believed to be one of the only
two places in the world currently home to Javan (or lesser
one-horned) rhinos, originally ranging from eastern India to
Vietnam and the Indonesian islands of Sumatra and Java. Ujong
Kulon National Park, Java, Indonesia, is thought to house about 60
such rhinos. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
