<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Golkar Congratulates PDI-P </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's Golkar Party Chairman
Akbar Tanjung Friday congratulated Megawati Soekarnoputri whose
Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI-P) has been confirmed
as the winner in the June 7 General election.
</P>
<P>
Tanjung said he wants a dialogue with the winning parties to
discuss various issues related to the upcoming general session of
the People's Consultative Assembly (MPR).
</P>
<P>
The MPR, the country's highest decision-making body, will meet
in November to elect the country's next president.
</P>
<P>
Golkar remains open to the idea of forming a coalition with
other political parties, Tanjung was quoted by the Antara News
Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian Election Committee (PPI) has completed the
national tabulation of votes on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
The PPI recorded a total of 105.78 million votes counted,
compared with 117.8 million registered votes and 4.42 million
invalid votes. The committee also found that 93.54 percent of the
registered voters were able to exercise their voting rights.
</P>
<P>
Data from the PPI showed PDI-P winning the election with 33.74
percent of votes, and Golkar trailing behind with 22.44 percent.
</P>
<P>
The PPI election returns are tentative because the final
results will be issued by the General Elections Commission (KPU).
The deadline set for the KPU announcement is July 21.
</P>
<P>
"The next process is the endorsement by the KPU. The PPI will
then calculate seats obtained by each party. After the seat
calculation is endorsed by the KPU, the contesting parties will be
notified," said PPI Chairman Jacob Tobing.
</P>
<P>
According to calculations by national newspapers, PDI-P is
expected to get 154 seats of the House of Representatives (DPR),
Golkar 120 seats, the United Development Party 59 seats, the
National Awakening Party 51 seats and the National Mandate Party
31 seats.
</P>
<P>
Forty-eight political parties took part in the election to
compete for 462 of the 500 seats in the DPR. The remaining 38
seats are reserved for the military, whose members do not vote.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
