<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Voter Registration Begins in East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The first day of voter
registration for East Timor's autonomy ballot was reportedly
running well, although only a few have turned up in registration
centers in the territory on Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Antara News Agency, the United Nations Mission
in East Timor (UNAMET) checked the documents brought by eligible
voters and interviewed each of them for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
A UNAMET personnel said many eligible voters are still busy
obtaining such documents as baptismal and marriage certificates
are needed in the registration process.
</P>
<P>
Those eligible to register are people who were born in East
Timor, more than 17 years old and their close relatives.
</P>
<P>
Chief of the UNAMET Ian Martin visited three districts in the
western part of East Timor during the first day of voter
registration Friday.
</P>
<P>
Martin was accompanied by U.S. Ambassador J. Stapleton Roy,
U.S. Deputy State Secretary for Asia-Pacific Affairs Stanley Roth
and U.N. civilian police chief Allan Mills.
</P>
<P>
Roth arrived in Dili, capital of East Timor, on Thursday to
carry out a direct assessment of conditions in the territory.
</P>
<P>
On the security in East Timor during the registration period,
Martin said the Indonesian Police have guaranteed that the
registration would be peaceful.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. is organizing a direct ballot in East Timor to enable
the East Timorese to accept or reject a wide-ranging autonomy
offered by the Indonesian government.
</P>
<P>
A rejection of the autonomy proposal will mean independence for
the former Portuguese colony.
</P>
<P>
East Timor was integrated into Indonesia in 1976 in a move
never recognized by the U.N.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan has delayed the direct ballot
in East Timor from its original schedule, from August 8 to either
August 21 or 22, due to logistical difficulties and security
problems. Voter registration was also delayed for two days from
Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
