<HEADLINE> Flood Ravages Central China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, July 16 (Xinhua)-- As of July 10, 37 people had died
in the floods ravaging central China's Hunan Province, according
to provincial flood control headquarters.
</P>
<P>
 The floods affected 10 million people, toppled over 70,000
residential houses, destroyed over 72,000 ha of farmland, and
caused direct economic losses totaling 3.1 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
 Since June 25, torrential rain have hit Hunan at the middle
reaches of the Yangtze River, raising water levels in major rivers
to the dangerous point.
</P>
<P>
 The water level at Chenglingji on the Yangtze shot up by more
than three meters in three days since June 30 and has been
hovering at the 34-meters level.
</P>
<P>
 Water levels along 1,046 km of banks astride the Yangtze and
at Dongting Lake are now above the danger level, and local army
troops and civilians are engaging in a tough battle against the
flood waters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
