<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Wild Goat Sighted in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- One of the most globally threatened
species of wild goat, serow or red serow, believed to be locally
extinct, has been sighted for the first time in 20 years in the
Matiranga Forest in Khagrachhari district, 184 kilometers
southeast of the capital city of Dhaka, the Daily Star newspaper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
An expedition of scientists from the International Union for
the Conservation of Nature (IUCN) and the Human Resource
Development for Advancement re-discovered the rare megafuna on
June 25 this year.
</P>
<P>
The serow is listed as an endangered species in the IUCN's red
list of threatened animals and in Appendix I of the Convention on
International Trade and Endangered Services, and it is nationally
protected under the Bangladesh Wildlife Preservation Act.
</P>
<P>
With its scientific name of capricornis sumtraensis, the serow
belongs to the horned ungulates family's caprinae sub-family.
</P>
<P>
Caprinae has intrinsic values as part of the ecology in a wide
range of distinct habitats, and its scientific interest is also
great because of their adaptation to the harsh mountain
environment.
</P>
<P>
Besides, serow has also great consumptive values as food,
medicine and trophy and at the same time it has non-consumptive
values for wildlife viewing and safaris.
</P>
<P>
From a purely anthropocentric perspective, the major value of
wild caprinae is that they are the ancestors of two of the most
important livestock -- domestic sheep and goats.
</P>
<P>
Most of the caprinae population are particularly vulnerable to
extinction because of their genetic isolation, specialized habitat
and low reproduction. There are threats from heavy hunting
pressure by locals and the loss of forest under-storey due to
clearing and collection of fuel-wood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 07:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 100 Illegal Immigrants Arrested in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 16 (Xinhua) -- More than 100 illegal immigrants
from Iraq and Syria had been arrested in Lebanon's northern port
city of Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
The 107 Iraqis and 14 Syrians, including women, children and
babies, reached Tripoli with the help of a network of middlemen
and waited to be smuggled to Greece, police said Friday in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
According to many of the immigrants, the middlemen, who are
still being sought, reportedly charged each of the immigrants 50
U.S. dollars and promised to get them to Greece by boat, the Daily
Star reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The refugees were staying in a public school where they were
taken by the police, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
They will be taken to the Abboudieh crossing point at the
Lebanese northern border once arrangements for sending them home
are agreed upon with the Syrian authorities.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus and Greece have complained in recent months that
boatloads of illicit immigrants entered the two countries from
Lebanon, especially the port of Tripoli. 
</P>
</TEXT>
