<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hyacinth Under Control in Zambia's Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The growth of the notorious water
hyacinth weed on Lake Kariba, the world's second biggest man-made
lake, has been put under control, the Zambia Daily Mail newspaper
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Zambezi River Authority as saying that 80
percent of the weed was killed after an initial spraying exercise
last August.
</P>
<P>
No further spraying is required because the whole Gache Ghace
and Nyaodza river mouths are cleared, said the authority.
</P>
<P>
The second phase in December last year cleared up some of the
remaining patches, leaving about 90 percent of the weed cleared in
Lake Kariba.
</P>
<P>
It said precautions were taken to avoid spraying close to
domestic water intake points and other sensitive areas and that
chemical control was adopted as the most effective short-term
control measure.
</P>
<P>
Water samples were taken before, during and after the exercise
for research.
</P>
<P>
The water weed had posed a great threat to the power generation
of the lake. Kariba power station is one of the biggest power
stations in Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chang Wins again in Challenger Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Michael Chang of the United
States eliminated his compatriot Taylor Dent, 6-2, 6-2 to advance
to the quarter-finals of the Safeway Challenger tennis tournament
in Aptos, California on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chang easily defeated 18-year-old Dent. The young American is
ranked 270th in the world.
</P>
<P>
Chang, ranked 59th, will take on eighth-seeded Cristiano
Caratti of Italy in the quarter-finals. Earlier in the day,
Caratti beat Israel's Amir Hadad, 2-6, 6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Tournament defending champion Cecil Mamiit, seeded second, was
forced to retire with a knee injury while trailing Michael Hill of
Australia in the third set. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
