<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0191 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's Oldest Panda Lives in Wuhan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 16 (Xinhua) -- An international Pedigree of
Giant Panda has declared a 37-year-old panda as the oldest member
of the rare species, according to today's Shanghai-based Wenhui
Daily.
</P>
<P>
The panda, named "Dudu," is now living at the Wuhan Zoo in
central China's Hubei Province. "Such an age for a panda is equal
to about 110 for a human," the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted zoo sources as saying that only three pandas
have reached over 30 years of age, and two died last year at the
Shenyang and Taiyuan zoos. The life span of a giant panda living
the wild is generally about 15 years, while a panda in captivity
can live as long as 25 years.
</P>
<P>
Dudu was born in 1962 at Chengdu, capital of southwest China's
Sichuan Province, and was moved to the Wuhan Zoo in 1972. The zoo
has set up a special team composed of 16 panda experts who have
done their best to ensure that Dudu will "welcome the new
millennium with humankind," the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Scientists are pursuing every possible means, including cloning
technology and preserving natural habitats, to try to bring the
species back from the brink of extinction. There are at present
only about 1,000 pandas in existence.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
