<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, July 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said he was
prepared for a "painful compromise" with Syria over the Israeli-
occupied Golan Heights, but would not retreat to the pre-1967
boundaries before the third Middle East war.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he told U.S. President Bill Clinton during their
talks on Thursday that Israel was ready in the coming weeks to
begin negotiations not only with the Palestinians but also with
the Syrians and Lebanese. (Barak-Clinton-Middle East)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
SANTIAGO -- Chile announced Thursday it will renew flights to
the Malvinas in mid-October following a package of agreements made
Wednesday between Argentina and Britain on the disputed territory.
</P>
<P>
Chile suspended flights to the Malvinas in March in protest
against the detention of Chile's ex-leader Augusto Pinochet in
London on October 16 last year.
</P>
<P>
Chilean Foreign Minister Juan Gabriel Valdes told the press
that the renewal of flights from Chile to the Malvinas was a
gesture of solidarity with Argentina. (Chile-Malvinas-Flights)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BRATISLAVA -- United Nations Secretary-General Kofi Annan said
here Thursday that the developments in Kosovo show that the role
of the United Nations on the world stage cannot be replaced by any
other organization.
</P>
<P>
"The world needs the United Nations not only at present but
also for a long time in the future," Annan said, on a two-day
visit to the country. (UN-Annan)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- Cambodian Foreign Ministry spokesman reaffirmed
here Friday that Cambodia has always adhered to "One-China" policy.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on Lee Teng-hui's recent separatist remarks
about cross-straits relations, the spokesman reiterated that "the
Royal Government of Cambodia will once again reaffirm our stance
that we support 'One-China' policy." (Cambodia-One China Policy)
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BUCHAREST -- NATO would not like to see boundaries of the
Balkan countries change, General Wesley Clark, NATO's Supreme
Commander in Europe, said Wednesday on a 5-hour visit here.
</P>
<P>
Clark's visit is believed for the purpose of easing the tension
aroused by what he had said in Budapest last month. He remarked
then that the Versailles Treaty which demarcated European
countries is out of date according to NATO's new strategy. The
remarks were considered a prelude to the alteration of Balkan
boundaries by Romania, who had already been fed up with the empty
promises made by NATO and the U.S. about security guarantee and
economic aid. (BC-Romania-Clark-Balkans) 
</P>
</TEXT>
