<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Faces Shortage of Mortuaries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 16 (Xinhua) -- As the death toll continues to rise
due to all sorts of diseases, AIDS-related ones being on the
forefront, Zimbabwe is now faced with a crippling shortage of
mortuary space.
</P>
<P>
Mortuaries in major referral centers are congested and they are
now storing more than four times as many bodies as their capacity,
the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The country's biggest referral center, Parirenyatwa Group of
Hospitals in Harare, has a capacity of only 42 bodies but now
stores about 200 bodies at any given time.
</P>
<P>
Health and Child Welfare Minister Timothy Stamps was quoted as
saying, " I would rather buy drugs than paying for building and
running mortuaries because we are in the business of looking after
the living not the dead."
</P>
<P>
"I am, however, not saying that mortuaries should not be
increased. We have encouraged urban councils to provide more
mortuaries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe is second to Botswana on the world list of countries
worst affected by AIDS. More than 700 people die every week from
HIV/AIDS- related illnesses.
</P>
<P>
The life expectancy of Zimbabweans, currently at 44 years, will
go down to 27 within the next 10 years due to the HIV/AIDS
scourge, a United Nations Population Division projection released
this week has revealed.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Development Agency human development report
shows that four sub-Saharan countries comprising Zambia, Botswana,
Uganda and Zimbabwe had experienced a 10 percent decline in life
expectancy between 1975 and 1997, the daily Herald newspaper
reported Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
