<HEADLINE> Balkan Boundaries to Remain Unchanged: Clark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, July 15 (Xinhua) -- NATO would not like to see
boundaries of the Balkan countries change, General Wesley Clark,
NATO's Supreme Commander in Europe, said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo is a part of Yugoslavia, he emphasized, adding that
there is no need for Romania and other countries to worry about
boundary alterations. At present as well as in future NATO would
not like to see them change, Clark told a news conference before
concluding his 5-hour visit here.
</P>
<P>
Clark met respectively with Romanian President Emil
Constantinescu, Prime Minister Radu Vasile and the acting Defense
Minister. He expressed appreciation to them for Romania's firm
support for NATO's position during the Kosovo Crisis.
</P>
<P>
Clark's visit is believed for the purpose of easing the tension
aroused by what he had said in Budapest last month. He remarked
then that the Versailles Treaty which demarcated European
countries is out of date according to NATO's new strategy.
</P>
<P>
Hungarian press reports of his statement made in Budapest
aroused uneasiness in Romania, which considered it a prelude to
the alteration of Balkan boundaries.
</P>
<P>
Clark argued that Hungarian media had quoted him out of context.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Clark didn't give any promise about Romania's
entry into NATO or NATO's aid to Romania, just like U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright, NATO General Secretary Javier Solana,
and German Vice-chancellor and Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer,
who visited Romania recently.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said Romania is displeased by Western countries'
empty promises. President Constantinescu has said that Romania
needs security guarantee and economic aid, instead of appreciation
and lip service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
