<HEADLINE> Dubai to Stick to 4 Percent Customs Duty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Dubai will maintain its current
4 percent customs duty regardless of political decisions Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) countries may take to unify their
import tax, an official of Dubai customs has said.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Obaid Saqr Busit, director-general of Dubai Customs, said
that he saw no rationale in hiking the tariff, the Khaleej Times
daily reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Dubai has been sticking to 4 percent, and we have no intention
now to increase the tariff when worldwide trend is to slash the
duty," the official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Dubai, the second largest emirate of the United Arab Emirates
(UAE), is the region's trade hub and distribution center
accounting for almost 80 percent of all reexport trade in the GCC,
which comprises the UAE, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar and
Bahrain.
</P>
<P>
The GCC countries are brewing a plan to unify their import tax
early next year, which might threaten Dubai's low tariff. 
</P>
</TEXT>
