<HEADLINE> Bangkok's Convenience Stores Join Crime Fight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 16 (Xinhua) -- About 600 7-Eleven convenience
stores in Bangkok have joined the city police's crime prevention
training program, the Bangkok Post reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The scheme was initiated to encourage members of the public to
help prevent crime and learn how to protect themselves, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
The program gives intensive training and lectures on relevant
laws, first-aid training and training on how to spot and identify
criminals and their vehicles.
</P>
<P>
With hundreds of 7-Eleven stores scattered in almost every
community in Bangkok, their managers should be able to help police
prevent crime throughout the city, president of the company was
quoted as saying, adding that 600 store managers of the chain had
joined the program.
</P>
<P>
The 7-Eleven chain has experienced a few minor robbery cases
since it started operations in Thailand over 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The company has been helping police work by having 1,000
checkpoints built and installed at 7-Eleven stores and elsewhere.
</P>
