<HEADLINE> Indonesia Needs New Karate Team Lineup for SEA Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesia Karate-Do Federation
(Forki) will hold a two-day competition to select athletes for the
20th Southeast Asian (SEA) Games squad in Brunei Darussalam next
month, The Jakarta Post reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Head coach Rustam Umbas said the selection would be held on
July 24 and 26 to pick the core squad of 21 of 35 karatekas.
</P>
<P>
Forki has been grooming 20 male karatekas for 10 divisions and
15 female karatekas for seven divisions to compete in the Games
from August 7 to 15.
</P>
<P>
The SEA Games organizers in Bandar Seri Begawan introduced a
new rule allowing each participating country to field only one
athlete per weight category in certain sports.
</P>
<P>
Separately, the National Sports Council (KONI) official in
charge of athlete development Mochammad Hindarto said the
organizers would not change the rule.
</P>
<P>
"They said they would stick to the rule," said Hindarto, who
has just returned from Bandar Seri Begawan to attend the chef de
mission technical meeting.
</P>
<P>
He said he hoped Forki could submit its new team lineup as soon
as possible but he did not set a deadline.
</P>
<P>
Rustam said if there were two athletes who tied in the
selection, Forki would review each karateka's achievements and
ranking this year before choosing one.
</P>
<P>
He also said Forki would call experienced referees, who often
worked in the regional competitions, to judge the selection.
</P>
<P>
"By having experienced referees, we hope they can prevent our
karatekas fighting so hard that they could injure themselves
during the selection. The Asian-level referees should know when he
should suspend and stop the game," he added.
</P>
<P>
Hindarto said the International Swimming Federation has given
its approval for the SEA Games to serve as the pre-qualifying
round for the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
"It was the secretary-general of Malaysia's National Olympics
Committee Sieh Kok Chi who informed me. I have told the Indonesian
Swimming Association about this matter but I have not received any
response," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
