<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Plans to Launch Venture Capital Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government is on the
move to launch a venture capital fund to raise money for small and
medium-sized enterprises in Mindanao and Palawan, the Today
newspaper said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Money raised through this venture will be invested in
enterprises that are not listed on the stock market and therefore
have no access to the equities market for capital formation.
</P>
<P>
Financial Assistant Secretary Ma. Eleanor de la Cruz has
already informed Securities and Exchange Commission Chairman
Perfecto Yasay Jr. of the plan to set up the private equities
fund.
</P>
<P>
The fund, to be called Eaga Philippine Fund, will be a
close-end venture investing strictly in private equities.
</P>
<P>
It will be incorporated as a limited company with an authorized
capital of 500 million pesos (12 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The fund's shares will be available to both Filipino and
foreign institutional investors in two tranches -- one for local
investors, the other for foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
The Eaga Philippine Fund will be managed by Capital Advisors
for Private Enterprises Expansion Inc. and Assets Managers Inc. It
will have the sole responsibility and full discretionary authority
to invest fund subject to the fund's board of directors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
