<HEADLINE> Myanmar Airline Resumes Flight to Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar Airways International
(MAI), a Myanmar-Singapore joint venture, resumed its regular
flight between Yangon and Kuala Lumpur of Malaysia Thursday after
more than five months of suspension which started on February 1
this year.
</P>
<P>
The twice-a-week flight on Thursday and Sunday is being
operated again with the use of Boeing 737-400 aircraft, The New
Light of Myanmar official newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The MAI started flying the Yangon-Kuala Lumpur route in 1993.
Later in November 1996, the Malaysian Airline System (MAS) joined
the same flight twice a week.
</P>
<P>
The MAI, a joint venture airline between the state-run Myanmar
Airways and the Highsonic Enterprise Private Ltd. of Singapore,
has been flying externally with Boeing 737-400 aircraft leased
from the MAS, to seven destinations -- Bangkok of Thailand, Hong
Kong, Dhaka of Bangladesh, Kuala Lumpur, Singapore, Kunming in
southwest China and Jakarta of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The MAI's Yangon-Kunming flight is learnt to have been
suspended for a time for unfavorable business operation.
</P>
<P>
Other foreign airlines that have regular flights to Yangon
include Biman (Bangladesh), Royal Brunei Airlines, Air China, Druk
Air (Bhutan), Indian Airlines, Lao Aviation Co., All Nippon
Airways (Japan), Pakistan International Airways, Silk Air
(Singapore) and Thai Airways International.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Myanmar and Macao signed a bilateral air services
agreement in Yangon in March this year to open flight between them
for thrice a week.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar Consular-General in Hong Kong U Hla Than said recently
that Myanmar and Macao are trying to inaugurate the flight before
Macao returns to China on December 20 this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
