<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Calls for Compensation of Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- The Kosovo crisis brought Bulgaria
big economic losses, Bulgarian Trade and Tourism Minister Valentin
Vassilev told visiting Southeastern Europe Stability Pact
Coordinator Bodo Hombach on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The losses, which were mainly a result of the crisis-triggered
decline in exports, amounted to 170 million Deutsche marks (89.5
million U.S. dollars), said the minister.
</P>
<P>
The Bulgarian minister asked for assistance from the Stability
Pact, which was endorsed at a European Union summit in Cologne,
Germany, last month to achieve stability in the Balkan region, to
construct a bridge across the Bulgarian-Romanian section of the
Danube.
</P>
<P>
Vassilev also asked to ease the access of Bulgarian goods to
the European and American markets and eliminate export quotas and
said it was necessary to establish a fund which would guarantee
investments in the region because after the Kosovo crisis the
Balkans are considered a risk area.
</P>
<P>
He gave Hombach a catalogue of Bulgarian projects and companies
wishing to take part in the reconstruction of the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
The coordinator, who is visiting Bulgaria as part of his tour
of the Balkan countries, also met Bulgarian President Petar
Stoyanov, Prime Minister Ivan Kostov and Foreign Minister Nadezhda
Mihailova.
</P>
<P>
Stoyanov told Hombach that Bulgaria attached great importance
to the participation of Bulgarian companies as subcontractors in
projects for the reconstruction of the region.
</P>
<P>
During the talks with Kostov, Hombach said Bulgaria will play a
leading role in the rebuilding of Southeastern Europe and that the
Stability Pact will not refer only to Kosovo but to all countries
of the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
