<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Ease Ban on Foreign Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government is set to lift
a restriction on foreign workers in certain labor-intensive
businesses after expiration of their permits next month, Bangkok
Post reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Illegal alien workers are expected to leave Thailand before the
August 4 deadline set by the Thai government last year.
</P>
<P>
A sub-committee on illegal workers will meet soon to determine
the businesses depending on illegal workers after the deadline,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
Employment of alien workers is aimed at alleviating labor
shortages in certain industries in Thailand, according to the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Thai deputy Prime Minister Korn Dabbaransi, the subcommittee
chairman, was quoted as saying that the national committee chaired
by Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai will meet on July 19 to discuss
the proposal and ways to formulate a broader framework for hiring
alien workers.
</P>
<P>
Industries facing a labor shortage in Thailand include rubber
plantations, construction, agriculture, rice mills and prawn
farms.
</P>
<P>
Last year, the Thai cabinet eased restrictions on aliens
working in coastal fisheries and those employed in certain
businesses in 13 border provinces.
</P>
<P>
Over 90,000 alien workers from Myanmar, Laos and Cambodia have
been granted temporary permits in Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
