<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Industry Grows 9.4 Percent in First Six Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua)-- China recorded an industrial added
value of 970.3 billion yuan in the first half of this year, up 9.4
percent over the same period last year, said Ye Zhen, spokesman of
the National Bureau of Statistics.
</P>
<P>
State-owned enterprises and those in which the state has a
controlling stake saw their added value rise 7.6 percent. Foreign-
funded enterprises' added value shot up by 12.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
During the first six months, growth rate of the heavy industry
surpassed that of the light industry by 0.8 percentage points. The
heavy industry completed an added value of 558.2 billion yuan, up
9.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that China has made marked progress in
optimizing the industrial mix in the first half of this year,
reducing further the size of textile and coal industries.
</P>
<P>
Sales of industrial products also improved in the past six
months. Its sales rate against production moved up by 0.74
percentage points to 95.66 percent.
</P>
<P>
During the January-May period, industrial enterprises earned a
profit of 48.3 billion yuan, up 93.3 percent on an annual basis.
Meanwhile, loss of low-performing firms dropped by 12.5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
