<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hke071613 -Lethal Malaria Resurgence Worries Vietnamese Officials </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese health care officials are
worried over the resurgence of lethal malaria in Vietnam, the
Vietnam News English daily reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam wiped out the disease in the northern region from 1954
to 1962, but it came back with a vengeance in 1991, which saw 144
outbreaks with more than 1 million victims and 4,600 fatalities.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the efforts of the Vietnamese government and local
health care authorities, between 1992 and 1997, malaria outbreaks
fell from 144 reported in 1991 to only four in 1997. Meanwhile,
the death rate from the disease dropped by 97 percent.
</P>
<P>
Last year, however, malaria outbreaks mainly took place in the
four provinces of Quang Nam, Kon Tum, Lao Cai and Nghe An.
</P>
<P>
A total of 183 people died of malaria last year, mostly in
Vietnam's central provinces and the Tay Nguyen region.
</P>
<P>
There were 130,403 malaria patients nationwide in the first
five months of this year, 6.8 percent less than the same period of
1998. However, Vietnam's health care officials are worried about
the number of malignant malaria cases, which has increased to 625.
This represents a 51.7-percent increase over the same period of
1998. Meanwhile, the death toll has reached 64, a year-on-year
increase of 42.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese health officials said that the most recent upswing
in malaria cases can be partially blamed on the changing weather
conditions.
</P>
<P>
The weather has been unstable, with average temperatures
increasing from one to two degrees centigrade compared to the past
years. In addition, the rainy season has come early in central and
southern provinces, as well as in Tay Nguyen.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese health authorities also said that large-scale
migration between provinces hinders their efforts to control the
disease.
</P>
<P>
They urged the government to restrict the movement of migrant
laborers and increase investment in infrastructure and health care
to cope with the resurgence of lethal malaria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
