<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Lowers Economic Growth Estimate for 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's Department of
Statistics (DOS) has revised the country's economic growth rate
for 1998 to a mere 0.3 percent from the previously-announced 1.5
percent following revision in the methodology of estimating the
added value of the financial services sector.
</P>
<P>
Using the revised methodology, the DOS also cut this year's
first- quarter gross domestic product (GDP) growth from 1.2
percent to 0.8 percent, 0.4 percentage point lower than the
earlier estimation.
</P>
<P>
An Information Paper released Thursday by the DOS detailed the
revision in the methodology used to estimate the added value and
the performance of the financial services sector.
</P>
<P>
It also declared that the methodology will reflect more
accurately the performance of three financial industries:
stockbrokers, investment advisers (fund management) and insurance
services.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, the revised method for estimating the
added value of stockbrokers and investment advisers is based on
improved quarterly data sources on fees and commissions received
and the new methodology for the insurance services is motivated by
conceptual changes introduced in the 1993 edition of the United
Nations' System of National Accounts.
</P>
<P>
A DOS official said at a press briefing Thursday that the
methodological improvement in the way to measure the contribution
of the rapidly-expanding financial services sector will also bring
changes to the GDP growth forecast for this year.
</P>
<P>
The new economic growth forecast for this year is expected to
be announced by Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong in his national day
speech, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
