<HEADLINE> U.S. Chamber of Commerce Signs Accord with Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, July 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Chamber of Commerce President
Thomas Donohue signed an accord of understanding Thursday with his
Cuban counterpart before winding up his three-day visit to the
island country.
</P>
<P>
It was the first visit paid by a U.S. Chamber of Commerce chief
to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Donohue was entertained by Cuban President Fidel Castro
Wednesday night at a dinner, which continued until the early
morning of Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. delegation also met with Parliament President Ricardo
Alarcon and Cuban ministers in charge of foreign trade, industry,
tourism and investment, during his stay in the country.
</P>
<P>
Donohue met with students and teachers of Havana University
Wednesday, telling them that Cuba could overcome its economic
problems if the United States lifted its long-standing trade
sanctions and Cuba implemented free market policies.
</P>
<P>
"We believe it is time to open a new chapter in the relations
between the people of the United States and the people of Cuba,"
Donohue said at the university.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated his chamber's opposition to the U.S. trade
sanctions against Cuba that started in 1962, but asked Cuba to
carry out economic reform.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Chamber of Commerce was established in 1912 and groups
some 3 million firms in the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
