<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sets Free Artificially Bred Endangered Birds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Two ibises which were living in
captivity have been set free recently by an ibis breeding center
in Yangxian County, in northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
It marks the start of the country's drive to return ibises in
captivity to nature, said Lu Baozhong, an official of the center.
</P>
<P>
China plans to set six ibises free this year. The other four
are being trained to learn to live in wildness.
</P>
<P>
Ibis is an endangered bird native to Asia. There used to be
large flocks in most of China, Japan, and Russia, but today the
species is found only in China. Its population has grown from a
mere seven in 1981 to over 202, as a result of artificial
propagation and environmental protection measures.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, 65 young ibises have been born in Yangxian
County, bringing the total number to 202. The reproduction rate of
ibis has grown at an annual rate of 40 percent in recent years.
</P>
<P>
At present, some 100 ibises live in captivity. They are less
capable than wild ibises in finding food, seeking spouses and
avoiding attack of other animals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
