<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Has 1.6 billion U.S. Dollars of Unpaid Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government said its
tax owed in the period from 1995 to 1999 totaled 11.4 trillion
rupiah (about 1.6 billion U.S. dollars), The Indonesian Observer
reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Director General of Taxation Anshari Ritonga attributed the
huge increase in the amount of outstanding tax to the recording
system and taxation procedures.
</P>
<P>
Under the system, Ritonga said, the directorate general of
taxation cannot automatically write off tax owed by a bankrupt
company. It must first be declared overdue.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, tax owed by the bankrupt company keeps on
mounting.
</P>
<P>
"That's why the amount of tax owed keeps increasing even though
the company itself lacks the capacity to pay," Ritonga said.
</P>
<P>
Companies entitled to have their tax written off are those who
have lodged an application for bankruptcy with the court, and who
have sent copies of their statements to the state auction body,
and announced their bankruptcy in the mass media and reported
details of their cases to the directorate general of taxation.
</P>
<P>
"The huge amount of tax outstanding is also due to the tax
outstanding on the debts of ailing banks which have transferred
their bad credits to the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The fact that the banking regulations contain debt write-off
provisions does not mean that they are not subject to tax, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Loans that have been written off are still treated as income
on the part of the debtors, and are thus taxable. This is part of
the tax regulations," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
