her first Olympic participation, The Indonesian Observer reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Nothing is impossible. I want a better achievement than today,
" Juana told reporters upon her arrival at Jakarta international
airport on Thursday, along with the other team members.
</P>
<P>
With the Olympics being less than one-and-a-half years away,
Juana said she would train even harder. She may indeed go back to
South Korea for training.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old Juana's place in Sydney was ensured after
reaching the semi-finals at the World Championship in Croatia on
July 8-12, although she was denied further contests as she was
stopped by Kay Poe of the United States.
</P>
<P>
However, her success means she becomes the first Indonesian to
take part in Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
"I just leave (my fate) to God. I feel I'm very much prepared
for the tournament after training in South Korea for two months,"
said Juana, who took part in the flyweight class.
</P>
<P>
Juana may already have set her eyes on Sydney, but she may
first have to focus on a minor event as the taekwondo federation's
officials begin to ponder whether Juana needs to be included in
the Indonesian sporting delegation at the Brunei Southeast Asian (
SEA) Games next month.
</P>
<P>
"We will put forward Juana's name although the entry by name
has already been submitted to the organizing committee," the
federation's chairman Suharto said.
</P>
<P>
When asked whether the SEA Games plan could distract her
Olympic preparation, Juana said: "I'm ready for whatever
competition I'm told to play."
</P>
<P>
She won a gold medal in her first international career in
Jakarta two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia grabbed six of 16 gold medals on offer in taekwondo
events at the SEA Games two years ago. This year, the association
is keeping a low profile and only hopes for four of 16 golds at
stake. 
