<HEADLINE> Finnish Court Says News Agency Chief Guilty of Libeling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HELSINKI, July 16 (Xinhua) -- A Helsinki court on Thursday
handed down a suspended jail term of 45 days to the editor in
chief of Finland's FNB/STT News Agency, Kari Vaisanen, on a libel
charge.
</P>
<P>
The court said that a dispatch, written by sports reporter
Johanna Aatsalo-Sallinen and cleared by Vaisanen in January last
year, constituted a libel against Jari Rasanen, a famous skier of
the country. The dispatch alleged that Rasanen abused banned
growth hormone.
</P>
<P>
Aatsalo-Sallinen received a 30-day suspended sentence.
</P>
<P>
The court also ordered that the two journalists and the news
agency pay damages of 1.57 million Finnish marks (about 270,000 U.
S. dollars) to compensate Rasanen and 19 people related to the
case.
</P>
<P>
Vaisanen and Aatsalo-Sallinen defended themselves by saying
that their report was reliable but they refused to provide
adequate evidence in order to protect their source.
</P>
<P>
The agency said it will decide next week whether to appeal the
verdict. 
</P>
