<HEADLINE> 2,400-Year-Old Bronze Sword Unearthed in Shaanxi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have uncovered
a 2,400-year-old bronze sword in a warrior's tomb dating back to
the Warring States Period (475-221 B.C.) in northwest China's
Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
"The sword is the only item buried in the tomb along with the
warrior," said one local archeologist, adding that the ancient
weapon is half-a-meter long and has many nicks on the blade.
</P>
<P>
The handle of the sword is plated with chrome and decorated
with jade is carved in a pattern of clouds.
</P>
<P>
Experts believe the sword was made in the middle or late era of
the Warring States Period.
</P>
<P>
This discovery is a valuable addition to the study of ancient
Chinese weaponry and military history, he added. 
</P>
