<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress in Tibet's Human Rights Record (17) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
3. Improvement of Economic, Social and Cultural Rights
</P>
<P>
Since the implementation of the Democratic Reform 40 years ago,
the Tibetan people have been making every effort to develop their
economic, social and cultural lives with support from the Central
Government and people from all over China.
</P>
<P>
Tibet has witnessed fundamental changes in its overall social
outlook while the Tibetan people have been enjoying better
economic, social, and cultural rights.
</P>
<P>
The central government has always instituted preferential
policies to encourage Tibet's social and economic development, and
has also allocated large sums of capital and provided support in
technology and professionals.
</P>
<P>
Between the 1950s and 1997, the Central Government allocated
more than 40 billion yuan (4.8 billion U.S. dollars) to Tibet
while sending large amounts of goods materials to the region.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, the Central Government has allocated
over 1.2 billion yuan (144 million U.S. dollars) in financial
subsidies to Tibet each year.
</P>
<P>
In Addition to 43 projects aided by nine provinces and
municipalities with a total of 477 million yuan (57 million U.S.
dollars) in 1984, another 62 projects were also launched in 1994
by the Central Government and other parts of the country with 4
billion yuan (480 million U.S. dollars), with 60 of these projects
already completed.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, groups of cadres and technicians have been
sent to work in Tibet, and 15 provinces and municipalities have
launched regular Tibet aid projects, all of which greatly
advancing Tibet's social and economic development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress in Tibet's Human Rights Record (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Following is the full text of an
article entitled "Historical Progress in Guaranteeing Human Rights
in Tibet" by China Society for Human Rights Studies, marking the
40th anniversary of the democratic reform in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
This year marks the 40th anniversary of the Democratic Reform
carried out in Tibet and the abolition of serfdom in the region.
</P>
<P>
Forty years is but a flash in human history, but for Tibet the
past four decades were world-shaking for the changes that have
occurred in social development and human rights.
</P>
<P>
1. Historical Turning Point for Human Rights in Tibet
</P>
<P>
Prior to 1959, people living in the old Tibet ruled by the
Dalai Lama were oppressed and mercilessly exploited by the
backward feudal serfdom system, and human rights meant nothing to
them.
</P>
<P>
During the late 1950s and early 1960s, the Tibetan people, led
by and with support from the Central People's Government,
conducted a democratic reform of great and profound significance
and completely abolished the feudal serfdom system, carving out a
new era for the development of human rights in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The old Tibet was a society practicing a feudal serfdom system
combining political and religious power, which was darker than the
European Middle Ages. The officials, feudal lords, and senior
monks, who made up less than five percent of the population of
Tibet, owned all cultivated lands, range lands, forests, mountains,
and most livestock. They also held power over people's lives and
property.
</P>
<P>
According to 1959 statistics, temples and senior monks were in
possession of 80,960 hectares of cultivated land, 36.8 percent of
all the 220,000 hectares of land in Tibet. Feudal lords occupied
52,800 hectares of land, feudal officials including some monks
came into possession of 85,580 hectares of land, which
respectively made up of 24 percent and 38.9 percent of the total.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress in Tibet's Human Rights Record (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The 13-point Law and the 16-point Law, which were enforced for
several hundred years in old Tibet, divided people into three
classes and nine ranks. The inequality of people's social and
political status was therefore affirmed and safeguarded by law.
</P>
<P>
The laws stipulated that "people have three classes, and each
class includes three ranks." According to the codes, serfs, who
belonged to the lowest rank of the lowest class, would be arrested
if they attacked those of the upper rank.
</P>
<P>
The codes stipulated that "anyone who resists a master's
control should be arrested; a commoner who offends an official
should be arrested; anyone who voices grievances at the palace,
behaving disgracefully, should be arrested and whipped."
</P>
<P>
The penalty measurement and penalties dealing with people of
different classes and ranks who violated the same criminal law
were quite different.
</P>
<P>
According to the law concerning murder compensation, for
instance, the lives of people of the highest rank of the upper
class were valued in gold at the same weight as the dead body. The
lives of people of the lowest rank of the lower class, such as
women, butchers, hunters, and craftsmen, were worth a straw rope.
</P>
<P>
In the law concerning compensation for injury, it was
stipulated that a servant who injured his or her master's hands or
feet must have his or her hands or feet chopped off. A master who
injured a servant was only responsible for the medical treatment
of the wound, with no other compensation required.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress in Tibet's Human Rights Record (18) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Statistics indicate that the gross domestic product of Tibet
reached 9.118 billion yuan (109 million U.S. dollars) last year, a
47.1-fold increase over 1959.
</P>
<P>
Investment in infrastructure projects came to 3.66 billion yuan
(440 million U.S. dollars) in 1998, 468 times greater than the
figure for 1958, before the Democratic Reform was launched.
</P>
<P>
Also last year, regional local revenue reached 364 million yuan
(43 million U.S. dollars), 96 times more than in 1958.
</P>
<P>
There was no modern industry in old Tibet, and the region had
only one small power station with a generating capacity of 92
kilowatts, a small military machinery plant, and a small mint,
with a total of 100 employees.
</P>
<P>
Now, Tibet has over 300 factories engaging in dozens of modern
industries such as power generating, mining, cement, leather
processing, textiles, food processing, and building materials.
State-owned factories employ over 50,000 workers and have begun to
be modernized while retaining Tibetan characteristics.
</P>
<P>
Industrial output value in Tibet last year reached 1.365
billion yuan (164 million U.S. dollars), up 31 times over 1959.
</P>
<P>
Prior to its peaceful liberation, Tibet was a land of backward
communications without a single modern highway or permanent bridge.
</P>
<P>
Tibet now has a highway network with the regional capital of
Lhasa as its center, with modern roads to Qinghai, Sichuan, and
Yunnan provinces and the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region. There
is also a highway to neighboring Nepal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
