<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Preparing To Introduce Fuel Tax </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- A Ministry of Finance official
says that Chinese authorities have drafted a detailed plan to
introduce a fuel tax, which includes dismantling institutions that
levy fees on automotive and road usage and finding other jobs for
their personnel.
</P>
<P>
Authorities have already started closing down toll booths on
roads in and around cities and they plan to crack down on illegal
petroleum processing and distributing companies.
</P>
<P>
In the past year, China has done away with 26,710 unreasonable
fees that central and local authorities levied on enterprises,
which were worth 98.5 billion yuan (11.86 billion US dollars). The
government has also dealt with more than 18,000 violations of a
ban on unreasonable fees for enterprises and has penalized 1,273
officials involved and confiscated 240 million yuan worth of
illegal fees.
</P>
<P>
The campaign to stop fees levied by government departments in
order to increase State and local revenues will take 3-5 years to
achieve.
</P>
<P>
At a recent meeting of the Standing Committee of the National
People's Congress, a draft of an amendment of the Highway Law
failed to pass by only one vote less, but it postponed the passage
of a fuel tax. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
