<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress in Tibet's Human Rights Record (20) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The per capita living space for urban residents in Tibet now
has reached 14 square meters, five square meters more than the
country's average, and the per capita living space for rural
residents now comes to over 20 square meters, equal to the country
's average. The per capita living space for the residents of Lhasa
now exceeds 17.3 square meters.
</P>
<P>
Modern domestic appliances including colored television sets,
refrigerators, and telephones have become very popular in ordinary
Tibetan households.
</P>
<P>
Traditional Tibetan robes made of lamb and otter skin formerly
worn only by aristocrats are now common among ordinary Tibetans.
</P>
<P>
Before the peaceful liberation of Tibet, there were no modern
hospitals in the region, only three small officially run and
poorly equipped medical organs and a few privately run clinics
with fewer than 100 doctors and nurses.
</P>
<P>
Together with a total of around 300 Tibetan medicine folk
doctors, the region only had about 400 medical workers, less than
one doctor for every two thousand people.
</P>
<P>
In old Tibet, epidemic diseases such as smallpox, cholera,
venereal diseases, typhoid fever, scarlet fever, and tetanus was
prevalent frequently.
</P>
<P>
After peaceful liberation, and especially after the Democratic
Reform, the Central Government took steps to prevent these and
other diseases which seriously threatened the health of the people,
and they were soon basically put under control.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1960s, Tibet has wiped out smallpox, and the
incidence of several other epidemic diseases and many local
diseases has declined sharply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
