<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0268 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress in Tibet's Human Rights Record (19) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tibet now also has Bomda, Damshune and Gongkar airports with
flight routes from Lhasa to Beijing, Chengdu, Xi'an, Xining,
Chongqing and other Chinese cities. There are also international
flights between Lhasa and Kathmandu in Nepal.
</P>
<P>
In old Tibet, agriculture and animal husbandry were engaged in
with very low productive forces.
</P>
<P>
In 1952, the region's total grain output was only 155,000 tons,
and the total number of livestock was 9.74 million head. In
contrast, in 1998 the total grain output reached 850,000 tons,
there were 22.1 million head of livestock, and the output value of
agriculture and animal husbandry combined came to 4.38 billion
yuan (520 million U.S. dollars), 30.4 times greater than in 1959.
</P>
<P>
Before the launching of the Democratic Reform, more than 90
percent of all Tibetans had no houses of their own, and many serfs
were forced to borrow and beg for a living.
</P>
<P>
At that time, the urban areas of Lhasa consisted of only 20,000
residents and nearly 1,000 poor households including beggars lived
in tents made of shabby gunny bags on the outskirts of the city.
</P>
<P>
Now, life for the Tibetan people has been greatly improved. In
1998, the per capita disposable income of urban residents in Tibet
reached 5,438 yuan (654 U.S. dollars), higher than that of the
country's average for the first time.
</P>
<P>
The per capita net income of farmers and herdsmen reached 1,158
yuan (139 U.S. dollars) and the savings deposits of urban
residents came to 3.345 billion yuan (403 million U.S. dollars) in
1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress in Tibet's Human Rights Record (16) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In July 1987, the autonomous regional People's Congress adopted
the Regulation on Study, Use and Development of the Tibetan
Language in the Tibet Autonomous Region for trial implementation,
which clearly stipulates that both the Tibetan and Chinese
languages should be used in the Tibet Autonomous Region, with
priority given to Tibetan.
</P>
<P>
Today, all resolutions, regulations, rules, and decrees adopted
by the People's Congress of the Tibet Autonomous Region and all
formal documents and notices issued by the autonomous regional
government are promulgated in both Tibetan and Chinese.
</P>
<P>
The people's courts and procuratorates at various levels of the
autonomous region also protect the citizens' right to use their
own language in lawsuits. Lawyers and prosecutors are required to
use Tibetan when conducting lawsuits involving people of Tibetan
nationality.
</P>
<P>
Newspapers and radio and television stations also use both
languages, and most of the books edited and published in the
autonomous region are in Tibetan. Speakers of different languages
are treated equally in the recruitment of workers, cadres and
students, with priority always given to Tibetan speakers.
</P>
<P>
In schools in Lhasa as well as in prefectures and counties,
teaching is done in both languages, and below the county-level,
the Tibetan language is the teaching language, and Tibetan is the
main course of all schools at every level.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0270 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress in Tibet's Human Rights Record (15) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since China adopted the reform and opening up policy in 1978,
the State has allocated more than 300 million yuan and large
quantities of materials like gold and silver for the repair and
maintenance of Tibet's lamaseries.
</P>
<P>
For the renovation of the Potala Palace alone, the central
government allotted more than 55 million yuan during a five-year
period, the largest and most expensive renovation project for the
palace in hundreds of years.
</P>
<P>
The central government also provided 6.7 million yuan in
special funds, 111 kg of gold, 2,000 kg of silver and large
quantities of jewels for the renovation of the holy stupas and the
memorial halls for the 5th to the 9th Panchen Lamas, and 66.2
million yuan as well as 650 kg of gold, for the renovation of the
10th Panchen Lama's holy stupas and memorial hall.
</P>
<P>
The central and the autonomous regional governments also funded
the renovation and repair of such renowned Buddhist temples,
lamaseries or monasteries as the Jokhang, Zhaxi Lhunbo, Zhebung,
Sera and Gandain, which satisfy the needs of religious believers
in their conduct of religious activities.
</P>
<P>
More than one million worshipers make the pilgrimage to Lhasa
each year, and in famous monasteries such as the Jokhang, crowds
of believers can be seen praying, turning their prayer wheels, and
bowing to Buddhist statues. Family halls for Buddhist sutra and
niches for a statue of Buddha are set up in the houses of nearly
every believers.
</P>
<P>
The Tibetan nationality's freedom to use and develop their own
language has been effectively protected, and Tibetan is the common
language of the entire autonomous region.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress in Tibet's Human Rights Record (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The serfs and slaves, who made up more than 95 percent of the
population of Tibet, owned nothing, and without personal freedom
they had to leech onto manors of the lords, or else be slaves for
generations.
</P>
<P>
Under the feudal serfdom, serfs suffered from compulsory corvee
labor, taxation and usury imposed by serf owners and lived on the
verge of death. Incomplete statistics indicated the existence of
more than 200 categories of corvee taxes levied by the Gaxag (
Tibetan local government). The corvee assigned by Gaxag and
manorial lords accounted for over 50 percent of the labor of serf
households, and could go as high as 70 to 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
The serfs, with little income, often had to rely on money
borrowed at usurious rates to keep body and soul together.
According to statistics, usurious loans in total before 1958 were
almost twice the total output value of farming and animal
husbandry, and more than 60 percent of farmers and herdsman ran up
heavy debts, and the figure was as high as 80 percent for Chalba
households. In some villages, everyone was in hock.
</P>
<P>
Serfs were forced to flee from famines and became beggars, and
countless numbers died of starvation and disease. Crowds of
beggars, including the aged and women and children, were often
seen in cities and towns such as Lhasa, Xigaze, Nagqu, and Qamdo.
</P>
<P>
Serfs and slaves had no personal freedom or political status,
while the manorial lords, who owned living bodies of serfs, were
free to trade, transfer, present, mortgage or exchange serfs, who
were seen as private property.
</P>
<P>
The serf owners wielded the power of life and death over the
serfs and the power over their marriage. Male and female serfs
belonging to different lords had to pay a "redemption fee" in
order to marry, and the children of serfs were born as serfs for
life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress in Tibet's Human Rights Record (14) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
And in consideration of the Tibetan people's tradition allowing
polygamy and polyandry, the autonomous region approved the
Accommodation Rules for the Implementation of the Marriage Law of
the People's Republic of China, which insists on the principles of
free marriage and monogamy, but made accommodations that allow the
above-mentioned types of marriages to exist if they were formed
before the promulgation of the accommodation rules, and no party
to the marriage voluntarily applies for an end to the marriage.
</P>
<P>
The religious freedom of the Tibetan people is respected and
protected. The abolition, by means of the Democratic Reform, of
the political system which combined religion with politics
provides institutional guarantees for the Tibetan people to
observe religious freedom and conduct ordinary religious
activities.
</P>
<P>
During the period of the Cultural Revolution (1966-1976),
however, in Tibet as in other parts of China, the policy of
freedom of religious belief was disrupted. But when the Cultural
Revolution came to an end, the State adopted many concrete
measures to safeguard freedom of religious belief, resumed some
traditional religious festivals, and repaired many sites and
facilities for religious activities which ensured normal religious
activities in Tibet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
