<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress In Tibet's Human Rights Record (11) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tibetan women enjoy the equal rights as men in participating in
government and political affairs. Before the Democratic Reform in
Tibet, women in Tibet were at the bottom of the social ladder and
had no political status at all.
</P>
<P>
In old Tibet, local governments had codes stipulating that "
Women should not be given the right to participate in State
affairs, and slaves and women should not engage in military and
political affairs."
</P>
<P>
After the Democratic Reform, Tibetan women began enjoying
status and rights as equals to Tibetan men in accordance with the
Constitution and law.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that since the first general election in the
Tibet Autonomous Region, the participation rate for women in the
elections of deputies to the autonomous regional People's
Congresses has all along surpassed 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
At present, the proportion of female deputies at various levels
of the autonomous region's People's Congresses is above 15 percent.
At the end of 1998, the region had 22,525 female cadres, making up
32.8 percent of the total.
</P>
<P>
According to the Constitution and the Law on Regional autonomy
of Ethnic Minorities, Tibet, where Tibetans live in compact
communities, adopts regional autonomy and the people there enjoy
the rights of regional autonomy. The law also stipulates that the
chairman or vice chairman of the autonomous regional People's
Congress Standing Committee must be of Tibetan nationality, as
well as the chairman of the autonomous regional government and key
posts of governments at various levels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress In Tibet's Human Rights Record (10) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Those aged 18 have the right to vote and the right to be
elected, regardless of their ethnic status, race, sex, occupation,
family background, religious belief, education, property status,
or length of residence.
</P>
<P>
They can vote for people's deputies in townships, towns,
districts, and counties who in turn elect deputies to the national,
autonomous regional, and municipal People's Congresses. People get
involved in managing State and local affairs through the People's
Congresses.
</P>
<P>
Since the founding of the autonomous region in 1965, Tibetan
and other ethnic minorities deputies have accounted for some 80
percent of the total number of deputies to the People's Congresses
in the Tibet Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
In the present ninth National People's Congress, 19 deputies
come from the Tibet Autonomous Region, 80 percent of whom are of
Tibetan nationality and other ethnic minorities. Out of the
autonomous region's 450 people's deputies, 82.44 percent are
Tibetans and from other ethnic minorities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress in Tibet's Human Rights Record (23) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The social status of women has been greatly improved. The
Tibetan women who emancipated themselves in the Democratic Reform
have taken an active part in economic, social and cultural
construction and have gradually realized their equality with men
in social life. Statistics show that women account for 48.5
percent of those who have jobs in Tibet, and in rural and pastoral
areas, women make up over 60 percent of the work force. In urban
areas, over two-thirds of the women above the age of 16 are
employed.
</P>
<P>
Enterprises and institutions in the Tibet Autonomous Region
employ more than 15,000 women, or 39 percent of the total
employees, and among the professional personnel, 12,900 or 40.12
percent of the total are women.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, educational conditions for Tibetan women have
improved and the enrollment rate for girls has been increased from
45.43 percent in 1993 to 71.3 percent at present. The autonomous
region has 1,206 female university students, or 37.69 percent of
the total number of college students.
</P>
<P>
The tremendous historical change in Tibet since the launching
of Democratic Reform in 1959 indicates that the abolition of the
feudal serfdom system and the implementation of regional autonomy
for ethnic minorities are the basic reasons for the social
development and earth-shaking improvements in human rights there.
</P>
<P>
Restricted by natural, historical, and economic conditions,
many aspects of human rights conditions in Tibet have yet to be
improved. However, human rights conditions will be constantly
perfected along with social and economic development, as long as
Tibet adheres to the road of socialism with Chinese
characteristics and the implementation of regional autonomy for
ethnic minorities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress in Tibet's Human Rights Record (22) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The old Tibet had no schools in the modern sense, and only some
2,000 monks and children of the nobility studied in old government
and private schools. The enrollment rate among school- age
children was less than two percent, and the illiteracy rate was as
high as 97 percent. The Tibetan people were deprived of the right
to an education.
</P>
<P>
After the launching of the Democratic Reform in 1959, a modern
multi-layer educational system, including pre-school, primary and
middle school, as well as higher education, adult and secondary
vocational and technical school education, was gradually
established in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, Tibet had 4,365 schools with an
enrollment of more than 400,000 students by the end of 1998. The
enrollment rate of primary-school age children reached 81.3
percent, up nearly 80 percent over that of the old Tibet, and the
illiteracy rate dropped by 47 percent.
</P>
<P>
Education is free from primary school through university in
Tibet, and primary schools in the remote areas provide students
with free clothing and room and board. These measures have
effectively protected the Tibetan's right to an education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress in Tibet's Human Rights Record (21) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At present, hospitals and epidemic prevention clinics have been
set up in every county of the Tibet Autonomous Region, and
hospitals of traditional Tibetan Medicine and maternal and child
care hospitals (clinics) have been built in some counties. More
than 70 percent of the townships and 30 percent of the
administrative villages in the region have established their
hospitals and clinics respectively.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, Tibet boasted over 1,300 medical
establishments in 1998, 21 times as many as in 1959, and the
number of hospital beds increased 17-fold to more than 6,700.
</P>
<P>
There are now 2.3 beds and 3.57 doctors for every 1,000 Tibetan
citizens, all above the national averages.
</P>
<P>
The improvement of medical and hygiene conditions in Tibet has
effectively protected the Tibetan people's right to sufficient
health care, and statistics indicate that the death rate among
pregnant and lying-in women in the region dropped from 50 per 1,
000 in 1959 to 7 per 1,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
The infant mortality rate has fallen from 430 per 1,000 in 1959
to 36.77 per 1,000 last year, and the average life expectancy has
increased from 35.5 years in the 1950s to 67 at present.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Tibetan population has increased rapidly,
by 1,233,600, or up 193.98 percent, from 1959 to 1998, the highest
growth rate in Tibet in this century. Last year, the birth rate of
the region was 18.4 per 1,000, and the natural population growth
rate was 10.9 per 1,000, much higher than the national average.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990716.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress in Tibet's Human Rights Record (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, some people of the upper ruling clique in Tibet were
simply against the reform and preached that there would be no
reform for a long period of time and even forever. They attempted
to retain serfdom forever in order to safeguard their vested
interest.
</P>
<P>
Confronted by surging requests for democratic reform from the
Tibetan people, these rulers refused to adapt to public opinion,
but rather conspired with anti-China forces abroad to organize a
series of armed rebellions and splittist activities.
</P>
<P>
They murdered Central Government officials stationed in Tibet
and cruelly killed those Tibetan people who supported democratic
reform.
</P>
<P>
On March 10, 1959 they undisguisedly broke the 17-Article
Agreement, announced the "independence of Tibet," and launched an
overall armed rebellion.
</P>
<P>
Under such circumstances, the Central People's Government
together with Tibetan people stoutly put down the rebellion in
order to maintain the unity of the country and protect the
essential interest of the Tibetan people.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the preparatory committee for the Tibet Autonomous
Region on July 17, 1959 adopted a resolution for carrying out
democratic reform. A mighty movement was thereafter launched among
the masses to push democratic reform in Tibet.
</P>
<P>
The reform smashed the feudal serfdom system and helped
millions of serfs and slaves realize their dream of the right to
be the masters of their own affairs.
</P>
</TEXT>
