<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin started his three-day state
visit to Mongolia yesterday.
</P>
<P>
China and Mongolia should join hands to develop long-term and
stable bilateral relations based on mutual trust into the new
century.
</P>
<P>
This was agreed by visiting Chinese President Jiang Zemin and
his Mongolian counterpart Nachagyn Bagabandy at formal talks
shortly after Jiang's arrival in Ulan Bator, capital of Mongolia.
</P>
<P>
-- Officials at all levels must have a comprehensive and clear
picture on the present economic situations, Premier Zhu Rongji
said yesterday in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
They should also have a down-to-earth attitude to foster China'
s economic development.
</P>
<P>
Zhu was speaking to senior leaders of provinces, commissions
and ministries at a national work conference on economy.
</P>
<P>
 "Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- China yesterday again refuted the Cox Report, calling its
conclusions "utterly absurd" and contrary to the general knowledge
of basic science and technology.
</P>
<P>
Following the May 31 press conference on the report, the
Information Office of the State Council yesterday issued a 25,000-
word refutation containing more details.
</P>
<P>
"The Cox Report shows typical racial discrimination and a
reappearance of McCarthyism," said Zhao Qizheng, director of the
Information Office.
</P>
<P>
He added that "the report collected quite a few examples, but
they were either fabrications or distortions of facts."
</P>
<P>
"China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- China is expected to ease foreign exchange restrictions on
foreign-funded enterprises to stimulate foreign investment inflows.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, foreign-funded enterprises will
be allowed to use funds in their foreign exchange clearing account
as time deposits, a practice that has been banned up to now. This
will allow them to receive interest and have more freedom in using
these funds.
</P>
<P>
-- A sluggish second quarter has held down the growth of China'
s gross domestic product in the January to June period to 7.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
This figure is 0.4 percentage points lower than what the
National Bureau of Statistics spokesman, Ye Zhen, forecasted over
a week ago and much lower than 8.3 percent rise registered in the
first quarter.  
</P>
