<HEADLINE> Mexican National Bank Issues 200 Million Dollars Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's most important bank,
the National Bank of Mexico (Banamex), on Thursday announced the
issue of 200 million U.S. dollars of bonds in international
markets.
</P>
<P>
The bonds have a duration of three years. The first part of 170
million dollars of the debt will be repaid monthly at a floating
rate, and the rest will be repaid in single payments.
</P>
<P>
The bonds were issued at a time when at least two other Mexican
banks were facing bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
The Institute for the Protection of Bank Savings (IPAB) had to
put 1.3 billion dollars into the Serfin Bank, Mexico's third
largest and one of the two facing bankruptcy, to rescue it.
</P>
<P>
Banamex said the New York office of German bank Landesbank
Girozentrale (WestLB) is the operator of the new bonds, the Harris
Trust Company of New York is the trustee and the Bank of New York
is the agent for collection and payments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
