<HEADLINE> Jordan 100 Percent Sure He Is Retired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 15 (Xinhua) -- Michael Jordan said Thursday he
is 100 percent sure he will not return to basketball, according to
reports from Long Grove, Illinois.
</P>
<P>
"It's a hundred (percent). It's a hundred right now," Jordan
told reporters following his round of golf at the pro-am at the
Ameritech Senior Open, which started on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Jordan said that "That's the only way you guys will leave me
alone," he said. "I might as well tell you I don't anticipate
going back."
</P>
<P>
Since his retirement, Jordan has remained a very public figure.
He appeared at a handful of NBA games during the 1999 season and
admitted he felt a desire to compete again. But he said he has
found a perfect cure.
</P>
<P>
"I got a little itch during the playoffs so I just went and
played more golf," Jordan said. "As long as I'm busy, I don't
think about it. But when I stop and think about it, I do get a
little itchy. But I haven't really played, maybe only three times
over the course of the last year."
</P>
<P>
Jordan talked more about his growing interest in golf, which
may be his next professional endeavour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
