<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China Province Sees Strong Economic Momentum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The economy in central China's
Henan province is expected to grow 8.3 percent during the first
six months this year, 1.3 percentage points higher than the
national target.
</P>
<P>
China set its annual economic growth target at seven percent
this year, compared to eight percent last year.
</P>
<P>
The inland province chalked up 45.95 billion yuan in industrial
output value in the first half of 1999, an increase of nine
percent from the same 1998 period. The growth was 3.9 percentage
points faster than that of the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The state sector reported obvious upturn in performance during
the period, with the growth for output value increasing by 3.4
percentage points on an annual basis. Non-state sector continued
to grow at a rate of more than ten percent.
</P>
<P>
Industrial efficiency also improved, with total industrial
profits surging 24.3 percent on an annual basis to 8.58 billion
yuan and deficits declining 18 percent to 565 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
The summer grain output rose 10.6 percent to 23.18 billion
kilograms, with summer oil output expected to total 316,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
Residents in Henan are enjoying rising income and low
commodities prices. Income for urban residents rose six percent to
2,287 yuan during the six-month period, with income for rural
residents increasing 4.8 percent to 663 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Fiscal revenue for local governments continued to grow rapidly,
which rose 20.8 percent on an year-on-year basis to 10.3 billion
yuan during the January-June period.
</P>
<P>
Savings with all financial institutions increased by 32.43
billion yuan to 409.64 billion yuan, while outstanding loans rose
17.2 billion yuan to 405.03 billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
