<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0040 GMT, July 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on Thursday called
the collapse of Northern Ireland's peace process a setback and
urged the parties to keep trying.
</P>
<P>
"I share the regret that the people of Ireland and Northern
Ireland feel at the setback in the peace process," Clinton said in
a statement. (US-Ireland)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LUANDA -- The Standing Committee of Angola's Council of
Ministers decided Thursday at a meeting that the country will
implement an "emergency strategy" to resolve the problem of war
refugees, the number of which has reached over 1.7 million in the
southern African country.
</P>
<P>
A press communique, issued here Thursday by the meeting, said
given the remarkably reducing relief goods from the international
community, and the limited fund on the part of the government, the
Angolan authorities decided to turn the previous direct relief
into self-relief through production by the refugees themselves. (
Angola-Refugee-Relief Strategy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Belarussian President Alexander Lukashenko said
Thursday that the United States has already assumed a constructive
position on Belarus.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting in Minsk with Adrian Severin, leader of the
working group for Belarus of the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe's Parliamentary Assembly, Lukashenko said
Belarus welcomes the latest contacts with the European
organizations and with the United States, the Interfax news agency
reported. (Belarus-US)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The U.N. Security Council Thursday voiced its
appreciation of the effort by the U.N. Interim Administration in
Kosovo (UNMIK), which is in charge of ensuring the law and order
in the Serbian province.
</P>
<P>
In a statement read to the press, the president of the Security
Council, Hasimi Agam of Malaysia, said that "Members of the
Council welcomed the progress achieved in the implementation of
Security Council resolution 1244," adopted on June 10 in
endorsement of the UNMIK and the international peacekeepers known
as KFOR. (UN-Kosovo-Statement)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema on Thursday
viewed British-Argentine agreement on Falklands/Malvinas islands
in the South Atlantic as "a step of important progress" towards a
peaceful solution to the islands' disputed sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
The flights were halted after the British-Argentine War in 1982,
which left 1,000 servicemen on both sides dead. (Italy-Britain-
Argentina) 
</P>
