<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Service Firms Look for Revenues Beyond Y2K </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, July 15 (Xinhua) -- With the new millennium
approaching, professional services providers in the United States
are finding other areas to tap in order to replace Y2K services
revenue, according to a new report released this week.
</P>
<P>
San Jose, California-based market research firm Dataquest
surveyed leading professional services firms to determine what
their strategies for survival would be now that Y2K related
concerns have, for the most part, been tackled.
</P>
<P>
Dataquest's report found that participants, while planning to
continue offering Y2K services over the next 12 to 18 months or
until demand disappears, would focus more toward developing
offerings targeted toward e-commerce, legacy migration/conversion
and enterprise resource planning.
</P>
<P>
Many participating companies said they would actively seek to
form partnerships or purchase companies, which would allow them to
expand new services offerings or grow already established
practices.
</P>
<P>
Although each business development strategy is unique,
Dataquest said, there is one common theme embraced by all service
firms -- Using Y2K professional services as a stepping stone for
capturing new business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
